<head>
<title>chapter8</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>CHAPTER EIGHT </p>
<p><font size=5><strong>In Conclusion</strong></font> </p>
<hr>
<p>How shall we look ahead and shape Georgia's future? By first looking back. Grady Clay, radio commentator, veteran 
observer of cities and author of Real Places, says, &quot;figuring out how your place came to be is the first step to knowing what to 
do next....Keeping a running, truthful account of how places get shaped, shifted, thwarted, and aborted is one of the most 
important jobs in your city and mine.&quot; This is what historic preservation does. In faithfully preserving historic places we tell the 
true story of how our communities and state became the places they are today. Georgia's historic places provide our identity 
as Georgians. As the state continues to change at an ever-increasing pace, we need links with our past to provide a sense of 
self and of place. Preservation of historic resources provides economic benefits that cannot be duplicated by new 
development. Preservation encourages more sensible development patterns that make our communities more livable. Our 
vision for Georgia in the new century must include our historic resources. </p>
<p>The historic places that make Georgia special will not preserve themselves. If they are to survive in the face of rapid change, 
we must plan ahead and work together to ensure their survival. The task will not be easy, for preservation takes the long view 
in a society that looks for the quick fix. Preservation is a decision for quality of life, when most decisions are based only on the 
short-term bottom line. Preservation requires cooperation among many partners when the trend is toward separation and 
competition. But we must succeed. </p>
<p>What is the alternative? A Georgia where communities have disappeared into nameless, repetitive areas of endless sprawl, 
devoid of character. A Georgia whose major cities have lost their center to suburbanization. A Georgia whose children lose 
hope in the future because they have no sense of the accomplishments of their past. </p>
<p>Each community leader, preservation organization, historic property owner, preservation supporter, elected official, and 
Georgia citizen has a stake in the future of Georgia, and each of us has a vital role to play in preserving our heritage for the 
future. </p>
<p>The Historic Preservation Division will strive to fulfill its mission to promote the preservation and use of historic places for a 
better Georgia. The Division will do all it can to turn the new vision into reality. Whether this vision will one day come about 
will be determined by a thousand individual decisions. The choices we make and our commitment to the vision for 
preservation will decide Georgia's future. The future is now. Will we accept the challenge? </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p><a href="newvisio.htm">Table of Contents</a></p>
</body>

</html>
</DOC>
