<html>
<head>
<title>HPD Preservation Plan preface</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/whttxtr1.jpg"
bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align="left"><font size="5"><strong>PREFACE</strong></font><br>
</p>
<hr>
<p align="left"><br>
<font size="3">A new century looms before us. Already we begin
taking stock. What was the twentieth century<br>
about? What did we accomplish? What did it mean? How did we fail
and how did we triumph? <br>
Already we begin looking ahead. How will we shape the
twenty-first century? How will it shape<br>
us? Will it be more of the same, or will we make new and better
choices? We prepare to witness<br>
the end of an amazing era; yet we also anticipate the beginning
of something new. <br>
<br>
As we head toward 2000 and beyond, it is time to create a new
vision. A vision of community, of<br>
shared experiences and shared heritage. A vision of a sustainable
society rather than a throwaway<br>
one. A vision that blends what we treasure from our past
accomplishments and experiences with<br>
what we create from new ideas.<br>
<br>
Georgia ends the twentieth century as one of the fastest growing
and changing states in the union. <br>
We have grown so fast that we have not taken the opportunity to
stop and assess, to adjust our<br>
course, to decide if our choices have been best. Now is that
time. <br>
<br>
New plans are underway in Georgia for the future of our
communities, for new direction in state<br>
government, for new transportation systems, for the Atlanta
region to the year 2020, for coastal<br>
management, for economic development and for many other aspects
of Georgia. Planning for our<br>
future must include planning for the continuation and protection
of our heritage -- our historic<br>
places and cultural patterns that tell the story of who we have
been and who we are becoming.<br>
<br>
New Vision: The Preservation Plan for Georgia's Heritage is the
plan for the state historic<br>
preservation program administered by the Historic Preservation
Division of the Georgia<br>
Department of Natural Resources. It covers the final chapter of
the twentieth century, specifically<br>
the years 1996 through 2000. Yet it is more about the advent of
the new century than the end of<br>
the current one, for the future is now. The choices we make now
will limit the options and create<br>
the opportunities we will have when the new century arrives. <br>
<br>
This plan presents a new vision that is shared by many. It sets
goals that are designed to turn the<br>
vision into reality. It identifies actions that will help keep
open the options, remove the barriers,<br>
and create the opportunities that will allow Georgians to
preserve their historic places for a better<br>
future. The plan is intended to guide the direction and
activities of the Historic Preservation<br>
Division. Because it also represents the views and priorities of
preservationists throughout<br>
Georgia who participated in its development, New Vision: The
Preservation Plan for Georgia's<br>
Heritage can provide common direction for all organizations and
individuals who support the<br>
preservation of our historic places. <br>
<br>
How will Georgia grow and change in the new century? How will our
neighborhoods and our<br>
communities meet our needs and reflect our values? How will we
tell our story of who we are as<br>
Georgians? Historic preservation can provide some of the answers
to these vital questions. The<br>
Historic Preservation Division has adopted this plan as a
statement of policy direction and as a<br>
commitment to action for the protection and use of Georgia's
valuable historic resources. We<br>
invite the reader to join us in working together to turn the new
vision into reality for the<br>
betterment of Georgia. </font><font size="4"><br>
<br>
</font><a href="newvisio.htm">Table of Contents</a></p>
<p align="left"><a href="index.htm">Return to the HPD Homepage</a></p>
</body>
