<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>CHAPTER FIVE </p>
<p><font size=5><strong>Goals and Objectives for Preservation</strong></font> </p>
<hr>
<p>A plan is useful only if it is put into action. A vision of a better future is only a dream unless it is accompanied by ongoing 
commitment, strategic focus, and hard work to turn the vision into reality. Therefore the heart of The Preservation Plan for 
Georgia's Heritage is this set of goals and objectives that are designed to guide the Historic Preservation Division in doing its 
part to bring the collective vision for preservation into reality. Many other preservation partners must plan their own set of 
actions in order for the goals for preservation to be fully realized. Some suggestions for these actions are contained in Chapter 
6, A Call to Action. The objectives and planned actions in this chapter are those of the Historic Preservation Division. </p>
<p>GOAL 1: Achieve widespread public awareness and involvement in historic preservation in Georgia. </p>
<p>Annual Objectives </p>
<p>1.1 Increase awareness of DNR management, staff and boards of the value and means of preserving historic and 
archeological resources on state lands and water bottoms, with particular emphasis on the proposed Coastal Zone 
Management program. </p>
<p>1.2 Simplify survey, National Register, tax incentive, grant, and other forms and facilitate their use wherever possible. </p>
<p>1.3 Annually seek input from groups not traditionally involved in preservation - including American Indian, African-American, 
and physically challenged populations - in the development of priorities, funding, criteria, and historic resource programs of 
HPD. </p>
<p>1.4 Annually, through press releases, workshops, state conferences, publications and project assistance, increase the 
understanding that historic preservation is a factor in sustainable development through reuse of existing infrastructure, 
redevelopment of downtowns and intown neighborhoods, recycling of buildings, and reduction of landfills by reducing 
demolition. </p>
<p>1.5 Annually cosponsor with the Georgia Trust the statewide historic preservation conference. </p>
<p>1.6 Annually plan and hold events for Historic Preservation Month and Archeology Awareness Week in May. </p>
<p>1996 Objectives </p>
<p>1.7 By June 30, 1996, expand legislators' understanding of HPD programs and needs through sponsorship of annual targeted 
tours and meetings with key members of the Legislature during the DNR budget development process. </p>
<p>1.8 By December 31, 1996, establish an advisory committee on archeology to advise HPD on general archeological policy 
and program directions. </p>
<p>1.9 In April, 1996, participate in a statewide heritage education seminar sponsored by the Georgia Trust. </p>
<p>1.10 By December 31, 1996, design and implement a new communications strategy for HPD that articulates HPD's vision, 
strengthens external and internal communication, and promotes a better understanding of historic preservation to the media 
and the general public, including: cultivation of media contacts through regular press releases and story ideas; internal policies 
on workshops, conferences and publications; new logo and graphics design for all written materials; updating of Fact Sheets, 
Helplines and other handouts; implementation of a revised schedule and format for a regular newsletter and monthly news 
sheet and redefinition of HPD job responsibilities in this area; and  use of the electronic media to get the preservation message 
to a broader public. </p>
<p>1.11 In April, 1996, cosponsor with the Garden Clubs of Georgia a House and Garden Pilgrimage. </p>
<p>1.12 By May, 1996, establish regular preservation technology information sessions to promote awareness within the 
architectural community. </p>
<p>1.13 By June 30, 1996, develop a referral list of preservation consultants, in cooperation with other statewide organizations. </p>
<p>1.14 By December 31, 1996, complete an archeology heritage education project sponsored by the Society for American 
Archeology. </p>
<p>1.15 By December 31, 1996, revise the National Register application package to make it more user-friendly; clarify minimum 
documentation requirements; and simplify application and nomination procedures. </p>
<p>1997 Objectives </p>
<p>1.16 By June 30, 1997, develop a professional development program plan for all HPD staff -- for consideration by all DNR 
Divisions -- that includes the following: linkage to the University System, providing low-cost courses and training to state 
employees; advanced public policy training for top-level managers and program associates; on-site and off-site training; 
funding to support professional development of every HPD associate on an annual basis; formal orientation of new associates 
that covers all Divisions and responsibilities of DNR; and  cross-training of associates. </p>
<p>1.17 Host the Southeastern SHPO annual meeting in 1997. </p>
<p>1.18 By March, 1997, prepare and publish proceedings for the conference, &quot;Telling Her Story: Expanding the Past of 
Georgia's Women Through Historic Places.&quot; </p>
<p>1.19 By December 31, 1997, reconsider HPD priorities for National Register nominations, and offer regular workshops to 
professionals who prepare nominations. </p>
<p>1.20 By June 30, 1997, accelerate the rate and scope of identification and evaluation of historic properties to meet 
preservation needs. </p>
<p>1.21 By June 30, 1997, define a typology of historic commercial buildings. </p>
<p>1.22 By June 30, 1997, develop a memorandum of understanding with the University of Georgia on the management and 
expansion of the Georgia Archeological Site File. </p>
<p>1.23 By December 31, 1997, develop with GDOT a historic context on Georgia agriculture with special emphasis on 
agricultural outbuildings and landscapes. </p>
<p>1998 Objectives </p>
<p>1.24 In 1998, assist the City of Savannah in hosting the National Trust for Historic Preservation annual conference. </p>
<p>1.25 By June 30, 1998, produce a tourist's guide to publicly accessible archeological sites and exhibits in Georgia. </p>
<p>1.26 By December 31, 1998, conduct and distribute a study on economic benefits of historic preservation. </p>
<p>1.27 By June 30, 1998, make the HPD heritage education slide show and African-American heritage video available to 
school systems throughout the state. </p>
<p>1.28 In 1998, publish a book on historic places in Georgia associated with women, if funding is secured. </p>
<p>1.29 By January 1, 1998, in partnership with the Georgia Alliance of Preservation Commissions, the Georgia Trust, the UGA 
Office of Preservation Services, GMA and ACCG, seek additional funding and implement a strengthened local government 
preservation initiative, including increased delegation of regulatory functions, training for preservation commissions, a defined 
HPD Community Planning Assistance program, and annual preservation awareness training for local elected officials during 
their organizations' meetings. </p>
<p>1999 Objectives </p>
<p>1.30 In 1999, provide staff support for the Vernacular Architecture Forum annual conference if held in Georgia. </p>
<p>GOAL 2: Gather information about all historic resources in Georgia, and make the information accessible for planning, 
advocacy and educational purposes. </p>
<p>Annual Objectives </p>
<p>2.1 Annually promote and cosponsor the Georgia Centennial Farm program and incorporate information gathered through the 
program into the historic resource inventory. </p>
<p>2.2 Develop standard approaches to providing to the public information about historic and archeological resources developed 
as part of the Section 106 process. </p>
<p>1996 Objectives </p>
<p>2.3 In March, 1996, sponsor a conference, &quot;Telling Her Story: Expanding the Past of Georgia's Women Through Historic 
Places,&quot; to gather information about women's history and preservation. </p>
<p>2.4 By December 31, 1996, complete the final phase of the Georgia's Living Places project, including distribution of technical 
materials and a heritage education unit. </p>
<p>2.5 By December 31, 1996, develop a historic context on resources from the recent past. </p>
<p>1997 Objectives </p>
<p>2.6 By June 30, 1997, initiate development of a DNR/HPD Geographic Information System (GIS) for historic and 
archeological resources and preservation projects, to promote access and use of HPD data and program information by local 
governments, HPD, RDCs, state agencies, and others. </p>
<p>1998 Objectives </p>
<p>2.7 By June 30, 1998, develop on-line capability to allow libraries, universities, consultants, local governments, and 
non-profits to access information on HPD programs and on historic and cultural resources. </p>
<p>2.8 By June 30, 1998, develop a streamlined procedure for revising and updating National Register historic district 
nominations listed between 1969 and 1990, to add contributing properties, redefine boundaries, and/or extend periods of 
significance. </p>
<p>2.9 By December 31, 1998, complete an inventory of Civil War-related historic and archeological resources along the route 
of the Atlanta Campaign, including GIS capability, in cooperation with the Georgia Civil War Commission and the National 
Park Service. </p>
<p>1999 Objectives </p>
<p>2.10 By June 30, 1999, work with the Centennial Farm program cosponsors to create and distribute a publication about 
Georgia's Centennial Farms and agricultural heritage. </p>
<p>2000 Objectives </p>
<p>2.11 By December 31, 2000, develop at least three archeological contexts. </p>
<p>GOAL 3: Secure financial and legal tools sufficient to preserve the significant historic resources in Georgia. </p>
<p>Annual Objectives </p>
<p>3.1 Annually seek to increase to $5 million the Georgia Heritage 2000 grant funding, in order to meet existing needs for 
historic property rehabilitation, African- American heritage initiatives, local government initiatives, and a heritage museum 
assistance program. </p>
<p>1996 Objectives </p>
<p>3.2 By June 30, 1996, work with preservation partners to prepare draft legislation and a strategy for passage and 
implementation to allow for income tax deduction for rehabilitation of owner-occupied historic places. </p>
<p>3.3 By August, 1996, develop a central clearinghouse of information on economic incentives related to preservation. </p>
<p>3.4 By December 31, 1996, hold a training session on the tax credit process for consultants. </p>
<p>1997 Objectives </p>
<p>3.5 By December 31, 1997, hold regional training sessions on the state tax program for local tax assessors. </p>
<p>1998 Objectives </p>
<p>3.6 By June 30, 1998, seek the funding and support necessary to carry out the legally mandated underwater archeology 
responsibilities in Georgia. </p>
<p>GOAL 4: Strengthen and expand the coordinated network of all historic preservation organizations throughout the state. </p>
<p>Annual Objectives </p>
<p>4.1 Annually develop and distribute a list of research needs for studies, contexts, and reports that will further the preservation 
of historic places and advance the state historic preservation program in Georgia. </p>
<p>1996 Objectives </p>
<p>4.2 By June 30, 1996, work with preservation partners to prepare draft legislation and the strategy for passage and 
implementation for the Georgia Historic and Cultural Museum Program. </p>
<p>4.3 Establish better communication and coordination techniques with preservation and related organizations. </p>
<p>4.4 Define the HPD role and level of support for committees and task forces, including the Georgia Civil War Commission, 
the Georgia African-American Historic Preservation Committee and Network, the Georgia Council on American Indian 
Concerns, the National Register Review Board, the archeological advisory committee, and others, to achieve mutual goals 
and objectives. </p>
<p>4.5 By July 1, 1996, strengthen the visibility and role of the Georgia National Register Review Board, as the major advisory 
board of the Division. </p>
<p>4.6 By December 31, 1996, assist the Georgia African-American Historic Preservation Network in developing programs and 
actions that implement the &quot;Georgia African-American Heritage Initiative&quot; and Strategic Plan. </p>
<p>4.7 By December 31, 1996, develop agreements with local governments and RDCs, where warranted, to delegate to them 
Section 106 review in defined situations. </p>
<p>1997 Objectives </p>
<p>4.8 By July 1, 1997, restructure the Regional Historic Preservation Planning program and seek the funding needed to provide 
statewide coverage and full-time programs. </p>
<p>GOAL 5: Protect and use Georgia's historic places so that they may exist into the future. </p>
<p>Annual Objectives </p>
<p>5.1 Annually cosponsor with the Georgia AIA at least one Downtown Design Team visit to a Georgia community. </p>
<p>1996 Objectives </p>
<p>5.2 By June 30, 1996, work with HUD, the Georgia Housing andFinance Authority and the Department of Community 
Affairs to create an Interagency Task Force on Affordable Housing and Community Conservation, and continue 
implementation of the HPD Affordable Housing Initiative through directed technical assistance to CDBG applicants, a series 
of workshops on rehabilitation and design issues, and early identification and evaluation of historic resources in target areas. </p>
<p>5.3 By June 30, 1996, assist the Georgia Civil War Commission in integrating its land protection goals into the overall land 
protection goals of DNR. </p>
<p>5.4 By December 31, 1996, develop a system for ongoing training and information for DNR Divisions to assist them in 
protecting and interpreting historic and archeological resources owned by DNR according to current methods and laws. </p>
<p>5.5 By December 31, 1996, complete the special Flood Recovery Assistance program, including a video and report on the 
program. </p>
<p>5.6 By December 31, 1996, evaluate with the Georgia Trust the development of a program to draw attention and assistance 
to threatened and endangered historic properties. </p>
<p>1997 Objectives </p>
<p>5.7 In 1997, hold a workshop on the treatment and maintenance of tabby structures and ruins as part of the Southeastern 
SHPO meeting. </p>
<p>5.8 By January 1, 1997, convene discussions with the Georgia Department of Transportation on the development of 
alternative highway and bridge design standards for historic areas, to protect the character of these areas for the future. </p>
<p>5.9 By June 30, 1997, develop a disaster response plan for future emergencies, in coordination with the Georgia Emergency 
Management Agency and other organizations. </p>
<p>1998 Objectives </p>
<p>5.10 By January 1, 1998, evaluate opportunities and costs for HPD to develop a historic property easement program, and if 
warranted, plan for future implementation of the program. </p>
<p>5.11 By December 31, 1998, provide to all DNR Divisions an archeological survey system and financial structure for required 
ongoing archeological survey of state lands. </p>
<p>2000 Objectives </p>
<p>5.12 By June 30, 2000, develop a State-Owned Historic Resource Stewardship program, including state policy, funding, 
technical assistance, interpretation, and recommendations on State property acquisition. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
