</head>

<body>
<p>CHAPTER SIX </p>
<p><font size=5><strong>A Call for Action </strong></font></p>
<hr>
<p>The preservation of Georgia's historic resources cannot be accomplished by the Historic Preservation Division alone. The 
Division's mission is to promote the preservation and use of Georgia's historic places for a better Georgia. This plan is 
designed to guide the Division in carrying out its mission. Other purposes of the statewide preservation plan include providing 
information about historic resources and preservation to a new audience, and identifying the role others in the preservation 
network play in bringing the preservation vision into reality. Historic preservation organizations, state and community leaders, 
property owners, and preservation volunteers and supporters must develop their own plans for the future. However, these 
plans can be most effective if they are coordinated. The vision and goals in this plan are representative of the views of 
preservationists across Georgia. The vision and goals can become a point of consensus among organizations with different 
missions but similar interests. </p>
<p>This chapter does not attempt to tell others what to do; rather, it points out actions that others can take to address the 
important preservation issues in Georgia's future. </p>
<p>National Action Needed </p>
<p>Goal 1: Achieve widespread public awareness and involvement in historic preservation in Georgia. </p>
<p>Federal agencies and national non-profit preservation organizations must continue to improve information dissemination and 
outreach activities, including use of mass media and new technology to broaden the awareness and support for preservation. </p>
<p>Goal 2: Gather information about all historic resources in Georgia, and make the information accessible for planning, advocacy 
and educational purposes. </p>
<p>Continue federal funding for surveys and National Register nominations. </p>
<p>Assist with the development of Geographic Information Systems and other technological advances to share historic resource 
data. </p>
<p>Continue to develop heritage education curricula using National Register information. </p>
<p>Goal 3: Secure financial and legal tools sufficient to preserve the significant historic resources in Georgia. </p>
<p>Continue appropriations from the Historic Preservation Fund that provide the basic framework for many preservation 
activities using a highly effective public-private and federal-state-local partnership to deliver preservation services. </p>
<p>Enact legislation that would provide financial incentives for the preservation of historic homes and other resources that now 
have few incentives. </p>
<p>Goal 4: Strengthen and expand the coordinated network of all historic preservation organizations throughout the state. </p>
<p>Delegate more preservation decisions to the state and local levels but retain federal agencies' ability to protect national 
preservation interests and to mediate between competing state, local, public and private interests. </p>
<p>Goal 5: Protect and use Georgia's historic places so that they may exist into the future. </p>
<p>Focus more on training, increasing public awareness, and providing the legal framework and financial support for protection, 
rather than on control of preservation decisions. </p>
<p>Find solutions to technical preservation problems such as lead-based paint or successful sustainable development techniques, 
and rapidly distribute the information nationwide. </p>
<p>State Level Action Needed </p>
<p>Goal 1: Achieve widespread public awareness and involvement in historic preservation in Georgia. </p>
<p>Work in partnership with the Historic Preservation Division to more effectively communicate the preservation message to a 
broader audience. </p>
<p>Encourage and actively seek the participation of groups that have not traditionally been members of preservation 
organizations. </p>
<p>Develop partnerships with other organizations with similar goals, such as environmental groups, planning organizations, tourism 
organizations, and local government organizations, to encourage them to become active in preservation. </p>
<p>Goal 2: Gather information about all historic resources in Georgia, and make the information accessible for planning, advocacy 
and educational purposes. </p>
<p>Work cooperatively with the Historic Preservation Division to develop a Geographic Information System for historic 
resources so that data can be shared among state and other agencies, and historic resources can be included in State agency 
planning. </p>
<p>Contribute to the database of historic properties by carrying out studies and developing historic contexts identified as priorities 
by the Historic Preservation Division. </p>
<p>Seek federal and state funding for archeological site evaluation and recording throughout the state. </p>
<p>Goal 3: Secure financial and legal tools sufficient to preserve the significant historic resources in Georgia. </p>
<p>Support efforts to increase the Georgia Heritage 2000 funding to meet existing needs for rehabilitation, surveys and planning, 
and special initiatives. </p>
<p>Participate in national efforts to retain federal preservation law, programs and funding. </p>
<p>Provide ideas and assist in the development of new state and federal legislation that would provide new protection or 
assistance to historic properties. </p>
<p>Goal 4: Strengthen and expand the coordinated network of all historic preservation organizations throughout the state. </p>
<p>Actively participate in the Historic Preservation Division's annual planning and public participation processs. </p>
<p>Establish better communication and coordination techniques with preservation and related organizations. </p>
<p>Assist local governments and organizations to become more effective in preserving historic places, by providing funding, 
training, technical assistance, legislative support, and encouragement. </p>
<p>Goal 5: Protect and use Georgia's historic places so that they may exist into the future. </p>
<p>Join in the expanding efforts to identify the costs of sprawl, the benefits of sustainable development, and the role historic 
preservation plays in defining community character. </p>
<p>Expand the use of easements, charitable donations of property, and other property-owner driven techniques of protecting 
historic places. </p>
<p>Participate in training local governments, preservation commissions, and preservation organizations in the use of preservation 
ordinances, planning, appropriate rehabilitation, and other methods of protecting historic properties at the local level. </p>
<p>Encourage the use of community development funds for rehabilitation of historic properties for affordable housing, community 
centers, and other needed projects. </p>
<p>Encourage State agencies to follow a stewardship policy of using historic buildings and incorporating the protection of historic 
properties into the management plans for State-owned property. </p>
<p>Local Level Action Needed </p>
<p>Goal 1: Achieve widespread public awareness and involvement in historic preservation in Georgia. </p>
<p>Increase efforts to broaden the public's knowledge and appreciation for historic preservation. </p>
<p>Get children involved in learning about and protecting their heritage. </p>
<p>Keep elected and appointed officials informed of preservation projects and activities in your community and make sure they 
know the benefits preservation brings to your community. </p>
<p>Include new groups in local preservation efforts; broaden the definition of who in the community is a preservationist. </p>
<p>Publicly recognize and thank individuals, organizations and businesses that assist preservation efforts. </p>
<p>Team up with other organizations with shared interests. </p>
<p>Use markers or signs to identify historic properties, and market historic places as a destination for tourists, businesses and 
residents. </p>
<p>Goal 2: Gather information about all historic resources in Georgia, and make the information accessible for planning, advocacy 
and educational purposes. </p>
<p>Find out what historic resources exist, and keep the information current. </p>
<p>Share all new historic re-source inventory data with the Historic Preservation Division and the Regional Development Center 
to insure its use in planning. </p>
<p>Actively advocate for improved regional and local planning and sustainable development. </p>
<p>Review the local comprehensive plan to determine if historic resources have been adequately addressed, and if preservation 
goals are integrated into land use, housing, transportation, community facilities, and economic development goals. Be involved 
in updating the plan, and track the progress made in implementing the plan. </p>
<p>Nominate eligible properties to the National Register of Historic Places. </p>
<p>Advocate the inclusion in surveys and in planning processes any special resource types, such as archeological sites, American 
Indian historic resources, Civil War battlefields, African-American resources, or resources from the recent past. </p>
<p>Goal 3: Secure financial and legal tools sufficient to preserve the significant historic resources in Georgia. </p>
<p>Consider accepting delegated authority from the Historic Preservation Division for certain preservation decisions and 
programs. </p>
<p>Learn more about and promote the use of easements as an effective way to protect historic resources while providing 
economic benefits to the property owner. </p>
<p>Consider designating conservation districts as a way to preserve community character. </p>
<p>Develop local financial incentives for preservation, such as facade grants, land trusts or revolving funds. </p>
<p>Actively support statewide and national efforts to maintain the national and state preservation programs and funding on which 
local preservation efforts depend. </p>
<p>Support efforts to adequately fund the Regional Historic Preservation Planning program to provide statewide coverage and 
full-time services. </p>
<p>Join preservation advocacy organizations. </p>
<p>Goal 4: Strengthen and expand the coordinated network of all historic preservation organizations throughout the state. </p>
<p>Attend the annual statewide historic preservation conference, and bring a new member of the network with you. </p>
<p>Join preservation advocacy organizations. </p>
<p>Actively take part in the Historic Preservation Division's annual public participation opportunities for inclusion in its planning 
process. </p>
<p>Incorporate preservation into the mission of other organizations with similar interests. </p>
<p>Goal 5: Protect and use Georgia's historic places so that they may exist into the future. </p>
<p>Pass a historic preservation ordinance, establish a preservation commission, and apply to become a Certified Local 
Government. </p>
<p>Insure that local preservation commissions receive regular training, to more effectively protect local historic resources. </p>
<p>Join the Georgia Alliance and the National Alliance of Preservation Commissions. </p>
<p>Use available funds such as CDBG, ISTEA, Local Development Fund grants, and others to rehabilitate historic properties to 
meet community needs. </p>
<p>Learn how Section 106 and the Georgia Environmental Policy Act can help protect local interests and historic resources, then 
get involved in these processes. </p>
<p>Disseminate information on good preservation practices for historic property protection, restoration and rehabilitation. </p>
<p>Conclusion </p>
<p>Decisions to preserve or not preserve historic places are made at all levels of government. Policies made at one level of 
government affect the actions of another level of government. Private organizations can do certain things that public agencies 
cannot. Public agencies can provide certain services and assistance and enforce laws and policies that the private sector 
cannot. Preservationists in all spheres of influence depend on the cooperation of others to accomplish their goals. The same is 
true in Georgia. By agreeing to work in concert with one another to achieve the vision and goals of the state historic 
preservation plan, the effect of our efforts will be multiplied. Historic places thereby will have a better chance of surviving into 
the future.</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
