</head>

<body>
<p>CHAPTER SEVEN </p>
<p><font size=5><strong>The Planning Process</strong></font></p>
<hr>
<p>An effective historic preservation plan must do many things. It must represent the considered views of those who will 
implement it and those who will be affected by its implementation. It must consolidate the myriad issues now confronting 
historic preservation and anticipate how those issues will play out in the future. The plan must be strategic by focusing on the 
highest priorities, effectively addressing threats and taking advantage of opportunities. It must be practical, yet present a vision 
and goals that push us beyond current practices and ways of thinking. Of equal importance to the preparation and publication 
of a planning document is the planning process from which the document was created, and the ongoing planning process that 
results in implementation of the plan. Implementation of a statewide plan would be impossible unless its goals were shared by 
many in the preservation constituency throughout the state. </p>
<p>This Plan was developed as a successor to A Vision for the Future: The Georgia Historic Preservation Plan, published in 
1989. Preparation and implementation of a statewide comprehensive plan for historic preservation is required by the National 
Park Service for a State Historic Preservation Office's continuation in the national historic preservation program. The Historic 
Preservation Division is also required to produce an &quot;action plan&quot; to implement the DNR Strategic Plan, which was adopted in 
late 1995. This plan fulfills both requirements. </p>
<p>Public Participation Phase I </p>
<p>The planning process began in earnest in November, 1994 when the Historic Preservation Division distributed a questionnaire 
to seek the comments, concerns and priorities of the general public and preservation constituencies. Although less than 100 
responses were received, the questionnaires that were returned represented a broad spectrum of organizations, areas of the 
state, professional disciplines, volunteer activities, and perspectives. The Division also made three presentations to the Georgia 
National Register Review Board at progressive stages in the process, to present findings and get feedback from the Division's 
advisory board. </p>
<p>In January and February of 1995, a series of six Planning Forums was held in Decatur, Dalton, Savannah, Fitzgerald, 
Columbus, and Washington. The Forums were widely advertised through the print media and personal invitations, and were 
attended by 411 people from many communities and organizations. The Forums were structured to provide information to the 
audience, then to elicit through discussion, written responses, and voting, specific views on historic resources, preservation 
programs, threats to resources, opportunities for preservation, services from the Historic Preservation Division, and goals for 
this Plan. The Forums were lively, well-attended, and productive. They brought into focus the widely varying viewpoints on 
preservation and historic places, and the widely varying needs for preservation services throughout Georgia. </p>
<p>Following the Planning Forums, a Preservation Roundtable session was held at the Statewide Historic Preservation 
Conference in February, to present the top preservation goals that emerged from the Forums, and to ask the participants to 
suggest high priority objectives to help reach each of the goals. </p>
<p>In-depth interviews were then conducted during the spring with a selected group of Georgia's preservation leaders, bringing 
the first phase of public input to a close. </p>
<p>Data Collection and Analysis </p>
<p>After public comments were analyzed, they were presented to the Historic Preservation Division staff at a planning retreat. 
The public comments, other findings from data analysis, special reports on preservation topics, and the study of local 
comprehensive plans formed the basis for staff input into the Division's mission statement and the Plan's goals and objectives. 
Data on historic resources, historic contexts, and distinctive aspects of Georgia history that were covered in depth in the first 
statewide historic preservation plan, A Vision for the Future, were reviewed and updated, but remain valid. This data formed 
the basis for the summary information on historic resources and for the historic resource based goals and objectives in this 
Plan. </p>
<p>Plan Development </p>
<p>The written plan was developed throughout the summer and fall of 1995, based on the public input, historic resource data, 
and trends analysis that had been completed earlier. Highlights from this analysis were shared with the Georgia National 
Register Review Board, Georgians for Preservation Action, and selected preservation leaders for reaction as the Plan 
developed. The Department of Natural Resources Strategic Plan, which was in development at the same time, helped shape 
the Georgia Historic Preservation Plan. </p>
<p>Public Participation Phase II </p>
<p>The draft Plan was reviewed by a panel of readers selected to represent a broad cross-section of opinions, regions, 
professional expertise, and areas of interest in preservation. Comments and feedback from these thirty-seven readers were 
used in revising the Plan. </p>
<p>Plan Implementation </p>
<p>The Georgia Historic Preservation Plan is designed to be put into practice, not sit on a shelf. Therefore an annual Action Plan 
will be developed by the Historic Preservation Division. The Action Plan will include specific actions that HPD will undertake 
in order to achieve the goals and objectives of the Plan. Accountability for the actions is insured by input from the public and 
the Georgia National Register Review Board and by assignment of each action to an HPD staff member. In addition, the 
Georgia Historic Preservation Plan and the annual Action Plan will be widely distributed to interest groups and the public to 
encourage them to work in partnership to achieve the goals and the vision for preservation in Georgia. HPD will seek public 
input each year as it evaluates the Historic Preservation Plan and prepares the Action Plan. </p>
<p>Revising the Plan </p>
<p>The Georgia Historic Preservation Plan is designed to guide HPD's historic preservation programs, policies, and services 
through the year 2000. The effectiveness of the Plan will be continuously monitored, and the annual Action Plan will allow for 
adjustments each year. The overall Plan will be thoroughly re-evaluated in the year 2000 to determine its validity for the future. </p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p><a href="newvisio.htm">Table of Contents</a></p>
</body>

</html>
</DOC>
