<title>Nongame-Endangered Wildlife Program Home Page</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/whttxtr1.jpg" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p>[ <a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/index.htm">Home</a> | <a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/news.htm">What's New</a> | <a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/toc.htm">TOC</a> | <a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/feedback.htm">Feedback</a> | <a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/search.htm">Search</a> ]</p>
<h2><img src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/wrd.gif" align=left hspace=0 width=100 height=100>Nongame-Endangered Wildlife Program Home Page</h2>
<h3>Give Wildlife A Chance!</h3>
<p>It would be difficult to picture our state without songbirds or wildflowers to brighten our days, without wild 
places to revive our spirits, without eagles to show us how to slip the bonds of earth. Georgia&#146;s wildlife resources and their 
habitats enrich our lives daily.<br>
Nongame refers to all species of wildlife (both animals and plants) that are not legally harvested. In Georgia, there are 930 
species of wild animals, of which only 55 are game, and more than 3600 species of native wild plants. Combined, these 
species make up more than 98 percent of all wildlife in our state.<br>
Headquartered in Monroe County on the Rum Creek Wildlife Management Area, the Nongame-Endangered Wildlife 
Program conducts management projects benefiting nongame wildlife as well as programs educating the public about these 
species and their needs. Although a number of projects are directed at managing state- and federally-listed endangered 
species, a primary mission of the Program is to implement management practices which will ensure the survival of all species.<br>
The success of our efforts depends on you. Look with eyes that see the world around you! Note the colorful disguise of the 
butterfly, the magnificent flight of the falcon ... the graceful bow of the pitcher plant. Do a self-study of Georgia&#146;s wildlife. You 
can begin by getting to know more about the Nongame Program on the pages that follow!</p>
<hr>
<p>Terry Johnson, Program Manager<br>
DNR -- Wildlife Resources Division<br>
Nongame-Endangered Wildlife Program<br>
116 Rum Creek Drive<br>
Forsyth, GA 31029<br>
(912) 994-1438<br>
<br>
Background/Funding<br>
Calendar<br>
Watchable Wildlife<br>
Neotropical Migratory Birds<br>
Coastal Issues <br>
Endangered Species</p>
<p><a href="../index.htm">Go To Wildlife Resources Home Page</a><br>
<a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/index.htm">Go To DNR Home Page</a><br>
</p>
