<html>
<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>P3 Program Introduction</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="Gray_Textured.gif">
<h1 align="center"><img
src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/p2ad.gif"
align="absmiddle" width="100" height="100"><font color="#008040">Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division</font></h1>
<h2 align="center">Pollution Prevention Partners</h2>
<h2 align="center">Recognition Program</h2>
<hr>
<p>Pollution Prevention Partners (P&#179;) is a three level
certification program that recognizes and rewards continuous
pollution prevention performance and environmental improvement by
Georgia industries. Companies that qualify for the P&#179;
program demonstrate to their customers, employees, and community
a commitment to preventing pollution and waste, increasing
efficiency, and improving the environment. The P&#179; program is
administered by the Pollution Prevention Assistance Division
(P&#178;AD) of the Department of Natural Resources. </p>
<p>The Entry Level recognizes facilities or plants that
demonstrate a commitment to developing a successful pollution
prevention program. Facilities that apply for the Entry Level are
eligible for a free, on-site pollution prevention assessment and
assistance in qualifying for the program from P&#178;AD.
Facilities that qualify for the Entry Level are eligible for
recognition in P&#178;AD publications and will receive a
certificate. </p>
<p>The Achievement Level recognizes facilities or plants that
have established a pollution prevention program and are making
progress toward meeting reduction goals. Facilities that apply
for the Achievement Level are eligible for a free,
non-regulatory, on-site pollution prevention assessment and
assistance in qualifying for the program from P&#178;AD.
Facilities that qualify for and maintain the Achievement Level
will receive public recognition in P&#178;AD publications, a
plaque and up to a 10% reduction in hazardous waste trust fund
and Toxic Release Inventory fees paid to the Georgia
Environmental Protection Division (EPD) for one year. Facilities
that continue to show progress toward meeting pollution
prevention goals may receive up to a 10% reduction in fees in
each of two additional years. The savings from these fees must be
allocated to pollution prevention activities at the facility. <b>(The
ability of EPD to reduce fees is contingent upon approval by the
Georgia General Assembly and the Governor in 1997)</b> </p>
<p>The Model Level recognizes facilities or plants that are
industry leaders in pollution prevention. Model Level facilities
incorporate pollution prevention into daily business activities,
and have made substantial progress toward meeting pollution
prevention reduction goals. Facilities that apply for the Model
Level are eligible for a free, non-regulatory, on-site pollution
prevention assessment and assistance in qualifying for the
program from P&#178;AD. Facilities that qualify for and maintain
the Model Level will receive public recognition in P&#178;AD
publications, a plaque, a flag and up to a 25% reduction in
hazardous waste trust fund and Toxic Release Inventory fees paid
to EPD for one year. Facilities that continue to show progress
toward meeting pollution prevention goals may receive up to a 25%
reduction in each of two additional years. The savings from the
fees must be allocated to pollution prevention activities at the
facility. <b>(The ability of EPD to reduce fees is contingent
upon approval by the Georgia General Assembly and the Governor in
1997)</b> </p>
<p>Pollution prevention is defined by the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency (EPA) as &#147;the use of materials, processes,
and practices that reduce or eliminate the creation of pollutants
or wastes at the source.&#148; Examples of pollution prevention
activities include inventory management/purchasing procedures,
source reduction, process modifications, housekeeping/good
operating practices, material substitutions, redesign of product,
pollution prevention education/outreach, and in-process
recycling. Disposal, off site recycling or reprocessing of wastes
is not pollution prevention. </p>
<hr>
<p>Go to information about <a href="entintro.htm">Entry Level
Certification</a> &amp; <a href="entinstr.htm">Application
Instructions</a></p>
<p>Go to information about <a href="achintro.htm">Achievement
Level Certification</a> &amp; <a href="achinstr.htm">Application
Instructions</a></p>
<p>Go to information about <a href="modintro.htm">Model Level
Certification</a> &amp; <a href="modinstr.htm">Application
Instructions</a></p>
<p>Return to <a href="index.htm#p2ad">P2AD Home Page</a></p>
<hr>
