<title>About P2AD</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="Gray_Textured.gif">
<h1 align="center"><img
src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/p2ad.gif"
align="absmiddle" width="100" height="100"><font color="#008040">Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division</font></h1>
<h2 align="center">About P<sup>2</sup>AD</h2>
<hr>
<table border="0" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td width="100%">
        <p align="center"><strong>P&#178;AD's vision is reflected
        in the Division's formula for success message: </strong></p>
        <h3 align="center"><strong>P</strong><sup><strong>2</strong></sup><strong>
        = E</strong><sup><strong>3</strong></sup><strong> </strong></h3>
        <p align="center"><strong>Pollution Prevention =
        Efficiency, Economics, and the Environment </strong></p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>
<h3><strong>Mission Statement</strong> </h3>
<p>The mission of the Pollution Prevention Assistance Division
(P&#178;AD) is to develop programs and activities to facilitate
reduction of pollution at the source, and instill a pollution
prevention ethic which is consistent with the protection of human
health and the environment. </p>
<hr>
<h3>History of P&#178;AD </h3>
<p>In the 1980's, the prevailing philosophy dictated that
hazardous waste be managed through treatment and disposal methods
using pollution control technology. Accordingly, the Georgia
Hazardous Waste Management Authority (Authority) proposed to
build a hazardous waste management facility, including an
incinerator, to manage the state's hazardous waste. </p>
<p>There was significant opposition to this plan. Therefore, in
1991, the Authority restructured and expanded its mission to
include the development of programs to facilitate the reduction
of hazardous waste at the source through various voluntary
measures. With these programs in place, the Authority
subsequently determined that a state-sponsored hazardous waste
management facility was not economically viable or needed in
Georgia at this time. As a result, it was decided that the
Authority go dormant and pollution prevention continue as a state
sponsored program. Every two years the Division is required by
law to determine whether Georgia produces enough hazardous waste
to warrant revisiting the need for a state sponsored facility. To
date, a need has not been established. </p>
<p>The Georgia Pollution Prevention Assistance Division was
created by the Georgia General Assembly as a non-regulatory
Division of the Department of Natural Resources to begin
operation October 1, 1993. The Division was designated by
Governor Miller as a &quot;One Stop Shop&quot; for Georgia
businesses interested in voluntarily finding ways to reduce their
generation of solid and hazardous waste; emissions; and releases
of pollutants into the air, water, and land. To accomplish this
goal, P&#178;AD has developed a variety of innovative <a
href="can_do.htm">technical assistance</a> programs including,
but not limited to, planning, information center, workshops,
on-site pollution prevention assessments, and training. These
activities are designed not only to provide technical assistance
to companies, but also to guide them in developing pollution
prevention programs tailored to their specific needs. </p>
<hr>
<h3>P&#178;AD Staff </h3>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD's staff consists of 15 full-time personnel and
three contract personnel who bring a broad range of experience
and expertise to P&#178;AD's activities and programs. Many of the
staff have worked for state and local government, industry,
private consultants, and environmental organizations. The staff
has expertise in management of solid and hazardous waste, water
quality, recycling, industrial processing and design,
manufacturing, energy, agriculture and public relations. They
include environmental, mechanical, chemical, and agricultural
engineers; chemists; biologists; a lawyer; a public relations
expert, and policy analysts. </p>
<hr>
<h3>Core Strategies</h3>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD offers a variety of <a href="programs.htm">programs</a>
to assist Georgia's citizens, businesses, government, and the
general public in improving by preventing waste. The Division's
clients generally fall within four groups: the manufacturing
sector, the commercial and institutional sector, the agricultural
sector, and the public sector. Five core strategies represent
basic approaches employed by P<sup>2</sup>AD in conducting its
daily operation and assistance activities. They range from
ensuring public and business input into Division programs to
promoting technology transfer through outreach. The basic core
strategies of P<sup>2</sup>AD include: </p>
<p><strong>Actively Seek Public Input</strong> </p>
<p>To instill the pollution prevention ethic and reduce pollution
at the source, P<sup>2</sup>AD must develop programs which are
embraced by the public and private sectors. This is accomplished
when the these sectors participate meaningfully in the formation
and implementation of pollution prevention policies and programs.
P<sup>2</sup>AD routinely uses four public involvement approaches
to gather input into its planning process. These techniques are:
surveys, focus groups, work groups, and public comment. </p>
<p><strong>Operate a Responsive Technical Assistance Program</strong> </p>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD's pollution prevention program seeks voluntary
participation from businesses and others that generate waste. The
technical assistance is non-regulatory and is provided at no
charge to the client. The main elements of the technical
assistance program include an information center, telephone
technical assistance, and on-site pollution prevention
assessments. </p>
<p><strong>Proactively Identify Organizations in Need of
Assistance</strong> </p>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD is responsive to requests for assistance by
all businesses and other organizations. However, this approach
will not ensure that needed information and support is requested
by the most significant waste generators. These groups may not be
aware of technical assistance provided by P<sup>2</sup>AD. To
reach this array of potential clients, P<sup>2</sup>AD identifies
technical assistance needs of generators whose waste may have an
adverse effect on the public health, the environment, or may
strain the existing environmental management infrastructure. P<sup>2</sup>AD
seeks voluntary participation in its non-regulatory pollution
prevention programs by motivating businesses through tangible
technical and financial incentives and recognition for continuous
improvements. </p>
<p><strong>Unlock the Pollution Prevention Potential of
Businesses and Others </strong></p>
<p>To ensure the continuous implementation of pollution
prevention, it is important that organizations consider pollution
prevention in their daily business planning. This means that the
budgeting, purchasing, and other financial decision makers must
consider the true costs of managing wastes in addition to other
environmental management decisions. P<sup>2</sup>AD offers a
variety of services to assist businesses in making sound
decisions based on a comprehensive evaluation of their
environmental management issues. Some of these services include
on-site facilitation, assistance in understanding true waste
management costs, environmental decision-making tools, and
recognition for internalizing the pollution prevention ethic. </p>
<p><strong>Maximize Use of Existing Resources</strong> </p>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD uses existing resources through innovative <a
href="partners.htm">public-private partnerships</a> with the
university system; federal, state, and local government agencies;
industry and trade associations; and non-profit organizations to
enhance the spread of pollution prevention throughout the state.
Two existing technical assistance partnerships are focused
primarily on addressing the pollution prevention needs of the
industrial and the agricultural sectors. Several research
partnerships with major industrial clients are underway to
provide process improvements for Georgia's carpet and paper
industries. </p>
<p>The Georgia Environmental Partnership (GEP) teams P<sup>2</sup>AD,
the Georgia Institute of Technology's Economic Development
Institute (EDI), and the University of Georgia's (UGA) Department
of Biological and Agricultural Engineering to coordinate the
delivery of environmental solutions to Georgia business through a
regionally-based technical assistance network. GEP also works
closely with the Southeastern Environmental Resources Alliance
(SERA) to facilitate the transfer of Department of Energy (DOE)
and Department of Defense (DOD) technologies to the private
sector for commercial application to pressing environmental
problems. </p>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD also teams again with the UGA's Department of
Biological and Agricultural Engineering and the Cooperative
Extension Service to promote pollution prevention practices to
agribusiness and the individual farmer using outreach,
environmental assessments through Farm*A*Syst, and applied
research. </p>
<p><strong>Promote Education and Information Exchange Through
Outreach</strong> </p>
<p>Outreach is regarded as a key strategy for making the public
and private sectors aware of pollution prevention issues and
informing them of the programs and assistance which is available
to them in addressing these issues. This typically involves
developing, distributing, and presenting information to local
extension services, Chambers of Commerce, or local governments;
publishing newsletters; developing waste reduction guidance
documents; and participating in public and industry sponsored
workshops and seminars. </p>
<p>From October 1, 1993 through September 30, 1996, P<sup>2</sup>AD
staff have responded to over 750 technical assistance requests,
made presentations at over 200 events, and expanded the mailing
list of the Division's quarterly newsletter, <a
href="newnews.htm"><em>From the Source</em></a>, to over 5,700
organizations and individuals. </p>
<hr>
<p>Return to <a href="Index.htm#p2ad">P2AD Home Page</a></p>
<hr>
</body>
</html>
