<title>Southwire Holds Second Annual P2 Workshop and Awards</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="Gray_Textured.gif">
<h1 align="center"><img
src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/p2ad.gif"
align="absmiddle" width="100" height="100"><font color="#008040">Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division</font> </h1>
<h2 align="center">Southwire Holds Second Annual Pollution
Prevention Awards &amp; Workshop </h2>
<p align="center">[<em>From the Source - </em>Spring/Summer 1996]</p>
<hr>
<p>On Thursday, April 18th, Southwire Company held a pollution
prevention workshop and awards day to help increase the awareness
of pollution prevention and recognize employee efforts during the
past year. &quot;Our Pollution Prevention effort is critical to
expanding our business domestically and globally. We are
committed to a strategy of eliminating pollution and waste from
our manufacturing operations,&quot; said Win Hill, Director
Corporate Environmental Management. &quot;Each year we meet to
share our successes and recognize those who demonstrate
excellence in this effort.&quot; </p>
<p>The morning session was highlighted by presentations from
Steve Avary of Zep Manufacturing, and Tony Knick and Frank
Hollowell of Synthetic Industries, who shared their pollution
prevention / waste minimization success stories. Other
presentation topics were about waste cost accounting and ISO
14000 international environmental management standards. In the
afternoon, six Southwire facilities discussed their pollution
prevention implementation processes and results achieved to date.
Southwire established a corporate waste minimization / pollution
prevention program in 1994. The Southwire facilities then
implemented the program through the use of employee Corrective
Action Teams (CAT). For 1995, 15 Southwire facilities submitted
waste minimization reports to be evaluated for the awards day.
Criteria used to judge the reports included evidence of employee
involvement, wastestream assessment, evaluation of pollution
prevention options, technology transfer, and measurable results. </p>
<p>The six facilities selected as finalists were: Carrollton
Utility Products Plant and Carrollton Building Wire Plant,
Carrollton, Georgia; NSA, Hawesville, Kentucky; Southwire Company
Starkville Plant, Starkville, Mississippi; Southwire Specialty
Products, Osceola, Arkansas; and Southwire Machinery Division,
Carrollton, Georgia. After the six facility presentations,
Southwire presented 1995 CEO awards for pollution prevention.
Carrollton Building Wire Plant and NSA were selected for
Achievement Awards. The Excellence Award went to the Southwire
Machinery Division for their outstanding achievement in pollution
prevention. </p>
<p>Seventy Southwire managers representing all U.S. manufacturing
operations attended. Representatives from the Environmental
Protection Agency (EPA) and the Georgia Environmental Protection
Division (EPD) were also in attendance. &quot;Today shows how
important recognition and awards are to inspiring employees to do
their best,&quot; said Bob Kerr, P<sup>2</sup>AD Director.
&quot;The effort extended by the Southwire plants and the results
obtained far exceeded the value of the awards. Congratulations to
all the participants for their outstanding efforts.&quot; </p>
<hr>
