<html>
<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Neighborhood Environmental Partnership</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="Gray_Textured.gif">
<h1 align="center"><img
src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/p2ad.gif"
align="absmiddle" width="100" height="100"><font color="#008040">Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division</font></h1>
<h2 align="center">Neighborhood Environmental Partnership </h2>
<p align="center"><strong>by Susan Varlamoff, Outreach
Coordinator</strong> </p>
<p align="center">[<em>From the Source - </em>Spring/Summer 1996]</p>
<hr>
<p>In 1994, President Bill Clinton signed an executive order
titled &quot;Federal Actions to Address Environmental justice in
Minority Populations and Low-income Populations&quot;. According
to Robert Bullard of Clark Atlanta University, an expert in the
field of environmental justice, one effective way to improve the
health and safety of neighbors living in industrialized areas is
through an industry commitment to pollution prevention. In
Georgia, the City of Atlanta, Clark Atlanta University, and the
Pollution Prevention Assistance Division (P<sup>2</sup>AD) have
teamed up to develop and implement the Neighborhood Environmental
Partnership to improve the quality of life in low income minority
neighborhoods in industrialized areas of Atlanta. </p>
<p>Through this partnership, a pilot study will be established in
Atlanta to encourage local industries to implement pollution
prevention into their operations and to provide a vehicle for
community outreach. This will be accomplished by contacting
company managers through the mail and by phone to inform them
about the project. Workshops will be held for interested
businesses on pollution prevention and outreach techniques.
Likewise the communities within the pilot area will be contacted
to participate in the outreach component of the study. </p>
<p>This concept is not new. For example, the chemical industry
has learned that a poor public image can negatively impact
business. As a result, the Responsible Care program was
instituted by the Chemical Manufacturers Association to address
environmental concerns. The program has six codes which a company
must fulfill in order to participate in the Association.
Pollution prevention and community awareness are two of the six
codes. This program has significantly improved the image of
chemical manufacturers. The textile industry has developed a
similar program. Closer to home, P<sup>2</sup>AD has incorporated
community outreach into its three level certification program
which recognizes companies for pollution prevention initiatives.
In order to achieve the highest level, a company must do
community outreach. More and more companies are opting to
&quot;go green&quot; because it improves their image, the bottom
line, and the surrounding environment. </p>
<p>For more information about the Neighborhood Environmental
Partnership, please contact Susan Varlamoff at (404) 657-5208, or
Marilyn Johnson, City of Atlanta, at (404) 330-6755.</p>
<hr>
