<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Pollution Solutions - Spring/Summer 1996</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="Gray_Textured.gif">
<h1 align="center"><img
src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/p2ad.gif"
align="absmiddle" width="100" height="100"><font color="#008040">Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division</font> </h1>
<h2 align="center"><b><blink>POLLUTION SOLUTIONS</blink></b></h2>
<h3 align="center"><em><b>From the Source - </b></em><b>Spring/Summer
1996</b></h3>
<hr>
<p>This issue of Pollution Solutions is focused on household
hazardous waste. The City of Alpharetta began accepting
batteries, lamps, and ballasts from residents in January 1996. To
date, the Alpharetta 2-4-8 Household Hazardous Waste Collection
and Recycling program has collected 3,564 household batteries, 47
fluorescent tubes, and 7 ballasts from over 200 people. The
average person drops off 21 batteries. One participant drove over
40 miles one-way to drop off batteries. The next step is to move
towards a daily collection so that the program can better respond
to the citizen's needs. </p>
<p>The collection is open one Saturday a month for the citizens
of Alpharetta. Residents outside the city may bring their items
to the collection for a small fee. For more information, please
contact Dee West at (770) 410-5835. </p>
