<title>Entry Level Introduction</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="Gray_Textured.gif">
<h1 align="center"><img
src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/p2ad.gif"
align="absmiddle" width="100" height="100"><font color="#008040">Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division</font></h1>
<h2 align="center"><b>Pollution Prevention Partners</b></h2>
<h2 align="center"><strong>Entry Level Certification</strong></h2>
<hr>
<h3><strong>Application and Selection Process </strong></h3>
<p>To apply for the Entry Level, facilities must complete the
P&#179; Entry Level application and return it to P&#178;AD.
P&#178;AD is available, at no charge, to assist facilities in
qualifying. The forms will be reviewed at local offices of the
Georgia Tech Economic Development Institute (EDI). An EDI
representative may visit the facility to verify information. The
facility must have no outstanding environmental compliance issues
or violations with the Georgia Environmental Protection Division
(EPD). P&#178;AD will certify the facility's acceptance into the
P&#179; program at the Entry Level and provide notification.
Facilities that fail to qualify for the program will be notified
of the reason, and offered assistance in qualifying.
Certification is granted when the facility meets all Entry Level
criteria and upon approval of the application by P&#178;AD.
Certification is for one year from the date it is granted. To
assure that certification does not lapse, facilities wishing to
be recertified the following year must submit an application no
less than 30 days prior to the expiration date of the
certificate. Facilities wishing to move to a higher level may
apply at any time. </p>
<hr>
<h3><b>Qualifications</b> </h3>
<p>To qualify as an Achievement Level Pollution Prevention
Partner a facility must meet the following general requirements: </p>
<p>1. The facility must be located in Georgia. </p>
<p>2. The facility must have no outstanding compliance issues or
violations with the Georgia Environmental Protection Division. </p>
<p>3. Facilities must have pollution prevention plans with
numeric goals for reductions through pollution prevention and a
time line for achieving those goals. P&#178;AD must approve the
facility&#146;s reduction goals. <b>(P&#178;AD is available to
assist companies in developing pollution prevention plans)</b> </p>
<p>4. Only those programs and activities that meet the definition
of pollution prevention will be considered.</p>
<p>(Pollution prevention is defined by the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency (EPA) as &#147;the use of materials, processes,
and practices that reduce or eliminate the creation of pollutants
or wastes at the source.&#148; Examples of pollution prevention
activities include inventory management/purchasing procedures,
source reduction, process modifications, housekeeping/good
operating practices, material substitutions, redesign of product,
pollution prevention education/outreach, and in-process
recycling. Disposal, off site recycling or reprocessing of wastes
is not pollution prevention.)</p>
<p>5. Certified facilities must agree to allow P<sup>2</sup>AD
the opportunity to publish non-proprietary information about
their pollution prevention program. </p>
<p>To be recognized as an Entry Level Pollution Prevention
Partner, facilities must meet certain criteria that demonstrate
their interest in and commitment to establishing a formal,
facility-wide pollution prevention program. The requirements are:</p>
<p><b><u>Pollution prevention plan</u></b></p>
<p>The facility must establish a pollution prevention plan that
contains goals for reducing waste and emissions through pollution
prevention. The reduction goals will be used as criteria for
advancement in the program. P<sup>2</sup>AD must approve the
facility's reduction goals. (P<sup>2</sup>AD has model plans and
a sample Entry Level application available. P<sup>2</sup>AD is
available to assist companies in developing pollution prevention
plans.) </p>
<p><b><u>Management commitment</u></b><u> </u></p>
<p>Applicants must demonstrate management commitment to the
pollution prevention program by having the highest ranking
company officer at the facility sign the pollution prevention
plan. </p>
<p><b><u>Employee commitment</u></b><u> </u></p>
<p>Applicants must demonstrate employee commitment by creating
one or more pollution prevention teams of employees to develop
strategies for the program.</p>
<p><b><u>Employee awareness program</u></b></p>
<p>Applicants must notify employees of the facility's pollution
prevention program and motivate employees to participate. </p>
<hr>
<h3><strong>Rules/Guidelines </strong></h3>
<blockquote>
    <ol>
        <li>Facilities must reapply yearly and show progress
            toward goals. </li>
        <li>Facilities that fail to qualify may resubmit an
            application at any time. </li>
        <li>Applications for the P&#179; program are accepted
            year round. </li>
        <li>Facilities wishing to withdraw from the program may
            do so by letter or by not reapplying the following
            year. All rewards and recognition associated with the
            company's participation in the program will be
            terminated at such time. </li>
        <li>A facility may participate at the Entry Level for no
            more than three consecutive years.</li>
    </ol>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>Go to <a href="Entinstr.htm">Entry Level Application
Instructions</a></p>
<p>Return to <a href="p3intro.htm">Pollution Prevention Partners
Recognition Program Information</a></p>
<p>Return to <a href="index.htm#p2ad">P2AD Home Page</a></p>
<hr>
</body>
</html>
