<html>
<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Model Level Introduction</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="Gray_Textured.gif">
<h1 align="center"><img
src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/p2ad.gif"
align="absmiddle" width="100" height="100"><font color="#008040">Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division</font></h1>
<h2 align="center"><b>Pollution Prevention Partners</b></h2>
<h2 align="center"><b>Model Level Certification</b> </h2>
<hr>
<h3><b>Application and Selection Process</b> </h3>
<p>To apply for the Model Level, facilities must complete the
P&#179; Model Level application and return it to P&#178;AD.<b>
P&#178;AD is available, at no charge, to assist facilities in
qualifying.</b> The forms will be reviewed at local offices of
the Georgia Tech Economic Development Institute (EDI). An EDI
representative may visit the facility to verify information. </p>
<p>To be eligible for a reduction in fees, the facility must have
no outstanding environmental compliance issues or violations, and
be approved by EPD. After being notified that a facility has
applied for acceptance in the P&#179; program, each EPD Branch
will check the applicant&#146;s files. If the applicant has no
files or no violations documented during the previous 12 months,
the applicant will be certified as eligible for the P&#179;
program. If the applicant had a violation, the Branch will
determine if it was resolved expeditiously. If so, the
application will be certified. If the violation is unresolved or
if the applicant was resistant in resolving, the application will
not be certified. </p>
<p>P&#178;AD will certify the facility&#146;s acceptance into the
P&#179; program at the Model Level and provide notification.
Facilities that fail to qualify for Model Level status will be
notified of the reason, and offered assistance in qualifying. </p>
<p>Certification is granted when the facility meets all Model
Level criteria, EPD file review and upon approval of the
application by P&#178;AD. Certification is for one year from the
date it is granted. To assure that certification does not lapse,
facilities wishing to be recertified the following year must
submit an application no less than 30 days prior to the
expiration date of the certificate. Facilities wishing to move to
a higher level may apply at any time. </p>
<hr>
<h3><b>Qualifications</b> </h3>
<p>To qualify as a Model Level Pollution Prevention Partner a
facility must meet the following general requirements: </p>
<p>1. The facility must be located in Georgia. </p>
<p>2. The facility must have no outstanding compliance issues or
violations with the Georgia Environmental Protection Division. </p>
<p>3. Facilities must have pollution prevention plans with
numeric goals for reductions through pollution prevention and a
time line for achieving those goals. P&#178;AD must approve the
facility&#146;s reduction goals. <b>(P&#178;AD is available to
assist companies in developing pollution prevention plans)</b> </p>
<p>4. Only those programs and activities that meet the definition
of pollution prevention will be considered. </p>
<p>(Pollution prevention is defined by the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency (EPA) as &#147;the use of materials, processes,
and practices that reduce or eliminate the creation of pollutants
or wastes at the source.&#148; Examples of pollution prevention
activities include inventory management/purchasing procedures,
source reduction, process modifications, housekeeping/good
operating practices, material substitutions, redesign of product,
pollution prevention education/outreach, and in-process
recycling. Disposal, off site recycling or reprocessing of wastes
is not pollution prevention.)</p>
<p>5. Certified facilities must agree to allow P<sup>2</sup>AD
the opportunity to publish non-proprietary information about
their pollution prevention program. </p>
<p>To be recognized as a Model Level Pollution Prevention
Partner, facilities must meet Entry Level and Achievement Level
requirements and the following additional criteria: </p>
<p><b><u>Pollution prevention reductions</u></b><u> </u></p>
<p>The facility must have in place a pollution prevention plan
with stated reduction goals (goals must be approved by
P&#178;AD). The facility must achieve 50 percent of overall
reduction goals from the baseline year as stated in its pollution
prevention plan. Facilities must demonstrate reductions in all
categories of waste generated at the facility and improved
efficiencies in the use of utilities and water. (E.g., Facilities
with four categories of waste must show reductions in each
category - solid waste, hazardous waste, air emissions and waste
water. Facilities with three categories of waste must show
reductions in each category.) Reductions achieved only through
pollution prevention, as defined above, will qualify. Facilities
must also report cost savings, if any, related to reductions. </p>
<p><b><u>External pollution prevention practices</u></b><u> </u></p>
<p>The facility must show how it is promoting pollution
prevention to its clients and vendors. The facility must show
that its efforts to prevent pollution do not cause the transfer
of pollution to other facilities. The facility must show that it
is promoting pollution prevention in its industry. </p>
<p><b><u>Purchasing and Product Development</u></b> </p>
<p>The facility must show that it has incorporated pollution
prevention in its purchasing practices, and, if applicable, in
the development of new products. </p>
<hr>
<h3><b>Rules/Guidelines</b> </h3>
<p>1. Facilities must reapply yearly and show progress toward
reduction goals. </p>
<p>2. Facilities that fail to qualify may resubmit an
application. </p>
<p>3. Applications for the P&#179; program are accepted year
round. </p>
<p>4. Facilities wishing to withdraw from the program may do so
by letter or by not reapplying the following year. All rewards
and recognition associated with the company&#146;s participation
in the program will be terminated at such time. </p>
<p>5. Facilities may apply for Model Level status if they have
been an Achievement Level Pollution Prevention Partner for at
least two years. Facilities may also apply for this level if they
have met Achievement Level criteria for at least two years. </p>
<p>6. Facilities must meet Entry Level and Achievement Level
criteria in addition to Model Level criteria. </p>
<p>7. Applications must be certified by a Professional Engineer. </p>
<p>8. Facilities receiving a reduction in fees must sign a
statement acknowledging that those funds have been, or will be,
applied to pollution prevention activities. </p>
<p>9. To qualify for a reduction in fees, Large Quantity
Generators of hazardous waste must demonstrate a reduction in
hazardous waste generation. </p>
<p>10. To qualify for a reduction in fees, facilities with
reported releases defined in Section 313 of SARA Title III must
demonstrate a reduction in reported releases. </p>
<p>11. Facilities applying for a reduction in fees for the second
year must achieve 60 percent of overall reduction goals. </p>
<p>12. Facilities applying for a reduction in fees for the third
year must achieve 70 percent of overall reduction goals. </p>
<p>13. Facilities may participate at the Model Level status
indefinitely. </p>
<p>14. Applicants must inform citizens in the surrounding
community that the facility has applied to be a Pollution
Prevention Partner. </p>
<hr>
<p>Go to <a href="Modinstr.htm">Model Level Application
Instructions</a></p>
<p>Return to <a href="p3intro.htm">Pollution Prevention Partners
Recognition Program Information</a></p>
<p>Return to <a href="index.htm#p2ad">P2AD Home Page</a></p>
<hr>
</body>
</html>
