<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Fall 1995 Pollution Solutions</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="Gray_Textured.gif">
<h1 align="center"><img
src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/p2ad.gif"
align="absmiddle" width="100" height="100"><font color="#008040">Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division</font></h1>
<h2 align="center"><b><blink>Pollution Solutions</blink></b></h2>
<h3 align="center"><em><b>From the Source - </b></em><b>Fall 1995</b></h3>
<hr>
<p>In the last issue, we asked how you reduced or eliminated
cleaning prior to painting. The following is a list of
suggestions:</p>
<ul>
    <li>Improve housekeeping. Keep paint area free of
        contamination. Avoid handling of parts by employees prior
        to painting. </li>
    <li>Determine if cleaning is necessary. In some cases, the
        substrate is clean enough to paint without additional
        cleaning. </li>
    <li>Avoid using materials with protective coatings that must
        be removed prior to painting, such as preservatives used
        to protect products while in storage (i.e., oils, grease,
        and silicone). Vendors often ship materials with
        protective coatings. Work with these vendors to reduce
        the use of such coatings. In some instances, materials
        that require painting can be replaced with color-matched
        injection molding.</li>
</ul>
