<title>Pollution Prevention on the Internet</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="Gray_Textured.gif">
<h1 align="center"><img
src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/p2ad.gif"
align="absmiddle" width="100" height="100"><font color="#008040">Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division</font></h1>
<h2 align="center">P2AD, Pollution Prevention, and the Internet</h2>
<p align="center"><strong>by Mike Garruto, P.E., Pollution
Prevention Engineer</strong></p>
<p align="center">[Summer 1995]</p>
<hr>
<p>P2AD has found the Internet to be an extremely useful and cost
effective work tool, particularly the electronic mail (e-mail)
and World Wide Web (WWW) features. As most of you may not use the
Internet yet, I will provide some reasons why you may want to
explore it. There is a wealth of information available, including
resources on the topics of pollution prevention and waste
minimization. Unlike the past, using the Internet is now a simple
process with user friendly software and typical monthly
connection charges of $15 to $30. Of course, a fairly up-to-date
computer and modem are also requirements while local phone call
access to the Internet service provider helps keep costs down.</p>
<p>An Internet account will quickly pay for itself if you use the
e-mail feature to eliminate many overnight carrier charges and to
reduce long distance phone bills due to reduced fax machine use.
Text, spreadsheets, CAD drawings, graphics, and sound files can
be sent locally, nationwide, or around the globe to one person or
several almost instantaneously using Internet e-mail. </p>
<p>Please note that P2AD's e-mail address is <a
href="mailto:p2ad@ix.netcom.com">p2ad@ix.netcom.com</a>, and we
will be responsive to requests for information and services
through our e-mail in addition to the more traditional phone
contacts and personal meetings. One benefit of e-mail has been
the ability to increase our knowledge base by taking part in an
electronic mailing list comprised of P2 technical assistance
programs throughout the country. When confronted with a
challenging situation, P2AD's technical staff can pose questions
to experts throughout the country who may be aware of possible
solutions or previous research in the area.</p>
<p>One feature that is driving the explosive growth in Internet
use is the World Wide Web. The WWW basically provides access to
multimedia files provided by other Web users. Information
accessed may be supplied by government agencies, educational
institutions, private companies, not-for-profit groups, and
individuals. With the click of a mouse button, users can move
from one Web location to another throughout the world.</p>
<p>Recently P2AD, in conjunction with the Department of
Administrative Services, established a presence on the World Wide
Web at <bold>http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/P2AD/</bold>. It is our intent to
continually improve this online service to make it as useful as
possible to the public. Therefore, we welcome any and all
questions, comments, and suggestions.</p>
<p>Our Internet Web pages have several highlights. First, our
home page includes an introduction to P2AD. A home page typically
has graphics like the front cover of a book, an abstract about
the individual or organization, and a menu similar to a table of
contents. A second feature is the online availability of our
newsletter, &quot;From the Source.&quot; In addition, P2AD
provides the public with easy access to draft reports of work
group recommendations covering topics that affect how P2AD can
best serve its mission. Announcements for upcoming seminars,
society meetings, conventions, and training opportunities are
also accessible. Finally, P2AD is providing a page of
&quot;pointers,&quot; known as hypertext links, to other
pollution prevention and environmentally related servers. This
page can serve as an excellent starting point for research on a
variety of topics. To give you an idea of the type of information
available from these servers, I am providing a small sample of
worthwhile sites. If you already have Internet access, consider
using our home page as a timesaving means of linking to these
servers. If you have no idea what the Internet and World Wide Web
are all about, just talk to one of the millions of users to help
you get started. For those who have no interest in the Internet,
P2AD will still be able to utilize the Internet's resources to
help you by using it to communicate with experts and to research
specific topics related to your concerns. When you do visit our
web pages, please e-mail us with your suggestions or favorite
sites!</p>
<h4>Sample of World Wide Web Sites on the Internet</h4>
<dl>
    <dt>**URL: http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/P2AD/</dt>
    <dd>Site: Georgia Pollution Prevention Assistance Division </dd>
    <dd>Information available: As described in this issue's
        article</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dt>URL: <a
        href="http://wastenot.inel.gov/envirosense/ssds/ssds.html">http://es.inel.gov/ssds/ssds.html</a> </dt>
    <dd>Site: Idaho National Engineering Laboratories (funded by
        EPA grant) </dd>
    <dd>Information available: Solvent substitution software and
        databases including SAGE(the Solvent Alternatives Guide),
        HSSDS (the Hazardous Solvent Substitution Data System),
        and the Department of Defense P2 Technical Library</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dt>URL: <a href="http://www.tis.eh.doe.gov/others/chem.html">http://www.tis.eh.doe.gov/others/chem.html</a></dt>
    <dd>Site: Chemical Safety Information </dd>
    <dd>Information available: EPA Chemical Fact Sheets, MSDS
        Sheets for hundreds of chemicals, Environmental Health
        &amp; Safety technical reference library</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dt>URL: <a href="http://www.finishing.com/">http://www.finishing.com/ </a></dt>
    <dd>Site: The Home Page of the Finishing Industry </dd>
    <dd>Information available: Calendar of events, technical
        library, links to metal plating and finishing
        organizations and societies, and letters discussing shop
        problems</dd>
</dl>
<p>**URL is an acronym for Uniform Resource Locator. In simple
terms, a URL is a web page's address.</p>
<hr>
