<html>
<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>What Can P2AD Do For You?</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="Gray_Textured.gif">
<h1 align="center"><img
src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/p2ad.gif"
align="absmiddle" width="100" height="100"><font color="#008040">Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division</font></h1>
<h2 align="center">Technical Assistance</h2>
<hr>
<p align="center"><strong>What can P</strong><sup><strong>2</strong></sup><strong>AD
do for you?</strong></p>
<p>P&#178;AD offers businesses, industries, and local and state
government agencies technical assistance in developing and
implementing pollution prevention programs. Technical assistance
is given in response to phone inquires, electronic
communications, mail, workshops, seminars, and on-site visits.
Assistance is free, confidential, and non-regulatory in nature. </p>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD's <a href="bio.htm">technical staff</a> can
assist you with many aspects of pollution prevention, including,
but not limited to, the following:</p>
<ul>
    <li>reduction of waste</li>
    <li>reuse of waste</li>
    <li>recycling of waste</li>
    <li>equipment or technology modifications</li>
    <li>reformulation or redesign of products</li>
    <li>substitution of raw materials</li>
    <li>housekeeping and maintenance</li>
    <li>training and inventory control</li>
</ul>
<p>All requests for information and services can be directed to
our information manager, Jancie Hatcher:</p>
<ul>
    <li>phone - (404) 651-5120 or 1-800-685-2443</li>
    <li>fax - (404) 651-5130</li>
    <li>email -<a href="mailto:p2ad@ix.netcom.com">
        p2ad@ix.netcom.com</a></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>P</strong><sup><strong>2</strong></sup><strong>AD
maintains confidentiality of proprietary information and client
reports.</strong></p>
<hr>
<h3 align="center">P<sup>2</sup>AD's services include:</h3>
<h4 align="center"><a href="#Information Center">An Information
Center</a></h4>
<h4 align="center"><a href="#On-site Assessments">On-site
Assessments</a></h4>
<h4 align="center"><a href="#Employee Training Sessions">Employee
Training Sessions</a></h4>
<h4 align="center"><a href="#Seminars and Workshops">Seminars and
Workshops</a></h4>
<hr>
<h3><a name="Information Center">Information Center</a> </h3>
<p>The P<sup>2</sup>AD Information Center (Center) is the point
of entry for technical assistance. Answers may be in the form of
mailed publications, suggestions from staff, and referrals for
voluntary on-site assessments. </p>
<p>The Information Center, serviced by a technical staff person,
contains a library of more than 2,700 documents, journal
articles, and books pertaining to pollution prevention,
recycling, and household hazardous waste. These are used to
answer inquiries about specific pollution prevention problems.
All documents have been abstracted and catalogued in a database.
In addition to books and reports, the Center maintains more than
50 current periodical subscriptions and a collection of more than
70 videos. </p>
<p>P&#178;AD also maintains a database of pollution prevention
equipment vendors. New vendor files are added to the database at
a rate of approximately 20 every month. Currently the database
contains information on more than 200 companies and 64
consultants. </p>
<p>In addition to in-house resources, the Center has access to a
wide variety of outside knowledge. The staff routinely accesses
the holdings at the Georgia Tech and Georgia State University
libraries. P&#178;AD uses the services of the Waste Reduction
Resource Center (WRRC), a regional source for pollution
prevention information funded by EPA and the Tennessee Valley
Authority. Lastly, the staff uses the Internet (World Wide Web,
gopher sites, etc.) and electronic mailing lists to research
specific information for clients. When confronted with a
challenging situation, P&#178;AD's technical staff can pose
questions to the country's experts who may have a possible
solution or can provide contacts to furnish needed information. </p>
<hr>
<h3><a name="On-site Assessments">On-site Assessments</a> </h3>
<p>A visit to your facility by P<sup>2</sup>AD's engineers can
provide new insight into improving efficiency and reducing waste
for your operation. </p>
<p>In working with small companies, a P&#178;AD technical staff
person performs an assessment to identify waste generating
processes and waste streams. For larger companies, P&#178;AD acts
as a facilitator to guide company managers in a self-assessment
of their waste streams. The Georgia Tech Economic Development
Institute assists P&#178;AD staff in performing assessments as
needed. All information is confidential. </p>
<p>After an assessment is made, a written report or fact sheet is
provided to the company management offering options for pollution
prevention, estimated waste reduction, and cost savings. Report
recommendations may contain several or all of the following:
redesign of production methods, non-hazardous substitutes for
hazardous materials, advice on good operating and housekeeping
practices, strategies to reduce energy and pollutant loadings for
publicly owned treatment works, and cost benefit analysis and
payback period for pollution prevention initiatives. </p>
<p>Six months after the report is delivered, P&#178;AD conducts a
follow-up discussion with clients to learn whether the company
has implemented any of the suggestions presented and whether more
information is required. A company is not required to implement
any or all of the recommendations. Their involvement is strictly
voluntary. </p>
<p>To date, a wide variety of assessments have been performed at
companies ranging in size from less than ten to more than 25,000
employees. An assessment report varies, depending on the size and
complexity of the company's business or manufacturing processes.
Assessments have been completed for businesses in many different
sectors including auto parts and maintenance, pulp and paper,
textiles, metal fabrication, and chemical manufacturing. In
addition, the Division currently has established on-going
relationships with several large companies based in Georgia. </p>
<hr>
<h3><a name="Employee Training Sessions">Employee Training
Sessions</a> </h3>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD provides pollution prevention training on-site
for a company's personnel. In these sessions, a cross section of
the company's employees (i.e., environmental, financial,
purchasing, upper management, line workers) can be trained
together. P<sup>2</sup>AD staff teach team building, how to do a
self-assessment on waste reduction, full cost accounting of
waste, recognizing waste reduction opportunities, and financial
analysis of pollution prevention initiatives. The objective of
on-site training is to provide information and knowledge about
pollution prevention that will be retained and used by the
company in the future. </p>
<hr>
<h3><a name="Seminars and Workshops">Seminars and Workshops</a></h3>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD sponsors seminars and workshops throughout the
state on various pollution prevention and waste reduction topics.
Topics may be industry specific or general pollution prevention
information. Some examples of workshops conducted by P<sup>2</sup>AD
include solvent substitution; pollution prevention for the
aircraft, aerospace, and airline industry; and storm water and
pollution prevention for trucking facilities.</p>
<hr>
<p>Go to <a href="announce.htm">list of upcoming P2AD workshops</a></p>
<p>Return to <a href="index.htm#p2ad">P2AD Home Page</a></p>
<hr>
</body>
</html>
