<h4 align="center"><a href="#Radon">Radon</a></h4>
<p align="center">&#160;</p>
<hr>
<h3><a name="Manufacturing Sector">Manufacturing Sector</a> </h3>
<p><a name="Toxic"><strong>Toxic and Hazardous Waste</strong></a> </p>
<p>The Georgia manufacturing industry (Standard Industrial
Classification Codes 2000 to 3900) consists of more than 10,000
companies. Approximately 600 companies reported waste releases in
1994, with a total of 31,000 tons of toxic pollutants emitted to
the air, land, and waters of Georgia. Six manufacturing sectors
which release the most significant toxic chemicals were
identified from information contained in the Toxic Release
Inventory (TRI) report and the biennial hazardous waste report.
These high priority manufacturing sectors include: </p>
<ul>
    <li>Pulp and Paper Products (SIC 26) </li>
    <li>Chemical and Allied Products (SIC 28) </li>
    <li>Transportation Equipment (SIC 37) </li>
    <li>Rubber and Plastic Products (SIC 30) </li>
    <li>Fabricated Metal Products (SIC 34) </li>
    <li>Printing and Publishing (SIC 27) </li>
</ul>
<p>A staff engineer was assigned to each sector to determine the
manufacturing processes used by these industries and to research
and develop pollution prevention expertise and solutions which
could be applied across the sectors. The information gained
through comprehensive technical literature reviews, extensive
telephone surveys, and conducting follow up on-site assessments
at numerous businesses within the sector is being used to prepare
sector-specific information and workshops. These outreach tools
are targeted to overcome key pollution prevention impediments
identified through the sector assessment process. </p>
<p><a name="Solid Waste"><strong>Solid Waste</strong></a><strong> </strong></p>
<p>The US Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) estimates that
non-hazardous, industrial process waste constituted over 57% of
the total solid waste generated in the United States in 1985.
About 39% consisted of special wastes (e.g. fly ash, mining
wastes), 2% was regulated hazardous waste, and about 2% was
municipal solid waste (MSW). MSW is generally thought of as
household waste; however, under the EPA definition commercial,
institutional, and industrial wastes (other than process waste)
can also be considered MSW. </p>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD has refocused some of its resources to address
the issue of non-hazardous, industrial solid waste reduction. The
approach will rely on existing activities, programs and
partnerships to develop and provide for solid waste reduction
options to Georgia manufacturers. </p>
<p>As a means to develop more effective reduction strategies, the
Environmental Protection Division, the Department of Community
Affairs, and P<sup>2</sup>AD launched a cooperative effort to
characterize the solid waste being disposed across Georgia.
On-site surveys have been conducted at 131 state landfills. A
goal of the survey was to obtain a &quot;snapshot&quot; of the
mix of residential, commercial, and industrial solid waste
disposed at each specific landfill. With 80 percent of the
surveys completed, preliminary data indicate about 22% of the
solid waste being disposed at landfills is from industrial
sources. The principal industrial waste streams observed were
textiles, construction and demolition debris, wastewater sludges,
wood wastes, food processing wastes, auto salvage wastes, and
waste from the manufactured housing industry. </p>
<p>A large amount of non-hazardous industrial waste is also being
disposed on-site at 43 private industry landfills in Georgia.
Little information is currently available from EPD files
concerning the character of the waste; however, a shift to
off-site disposal of this industrial waste could severely affect
municipal solid waste disposal capacity. Although EPD is
responsible for monitoring these landfills, P<sup>2</sup>AD is
available to assist companies wishing to reduce their waste
streams. </p>
<hr>
<h3><a name="C &amp; I Sector">Commercial and Institutional
Sector</a> </h3>
<p>As part of restructuring the solid waste responsibilities in
the state, P<sup>2</sup>AD is assuming the lead state role for
commercial and institutional solid waste reduction. Commercial
sectors include office buildings, retail, and service
establishments. Institutions include school, libraries,
hospitals, and prisons. According to Department of Labor
statistics, there were about 180,500 commercial businesses in
Georgia in 1995. As indicated above, P<sup>2</sup>AD, DCA, and
EPD conducted on-site surveys of 131 landfill sites across the
state to gather characterization information. The preliminary
data indicates that approximately 33% of the estimated 9 million
tons of waste disposed in Georgia's municipal landfills is from
commercial and institutional sources. The estimation does not
take into account the waste disposed of in those commercial
landfills which keep their disposal types and quantities
proprietary. </p>
<p>Using the survey results and supplemental information, P<sup>2</sup>AD
will seek to identify specific commercial solid waste streams in
order to develop waste reduction strategies and market
development opportunities. Both the waste types and quantities
disposed are important factors in this effort. It is likely that
the commercial and institutional solid waste program will use the
six basic strategies established by P<sup>2</sup>AD in addressing
waste streams for the manufacturing sector. </p>
<hr>
<h3><a name="Agricultural Sector">Agricultural Sector</a> </h3>
<p>Agriculture is a leading industry in Georgia contributing more
than $38 billion annually to Georgia's $180 billion economic
output. Agriculture, including the production, processing,
packaging, and transporting of farm products, employs
approximately one in six Georgians and almost half the state's
manufacturing jobs are in agribusiness. Georgia's top ten farm
commodities include commercial broilers, peanuts, cattle, eggs,
vegetables, dairy products, cotton, hogs, nursery/greenhouse, and
tobacco. Besides these commodities, the production and
distribution of farm inputs and machinery contribute an
additional $1.5 billion and employ about 15,000 people. </p>
<p>As one of the largest industries in Georgia, agricultural
production has significant potential for environmental
degradation. Contamination from agricultural practices is
estimated to contribute approximately 65% of all non-point source
pollution. Animals produced in Georgia generate an estimated 22
million tons of manure each year. In addition, yearly crop
production in Georgia uses approximately 1.67 million tons of
commercial fertilizers. Many of these nutrients, if not managed
and used properly, can degrade both the surface and ground water.
The $156 million worth of pesticides used in agricultural crop
production can also pose significant risk to environmental
resources. Agriculture also uses significant amounts of fuel,
oil, and energy, contributes millions of tons of sediment from
soil erosion, and can create many air quality concerns including
odor and dust generation. </p>
<p>The diversity of agricultural industries presents many
obstacles to the adoption of pollution prevention technologies. P<sup>2</sup>AD
recognized this need and allocated a budget to establish an
agricultural pollution prevention program in cooperation with The
University of Georgia's Biological and Agricultural Engineering
Department. The goal of the Georgia Agricultural Pollution
Prevention Program is to encourage the agricultural community to
actively practice voluntary pollution prevention with a
commitment to reducing emissions, waste, and the use of energy,
water, and dangerous materials to the greatest extent practical. </p>
<p>This program also functions using both responsive and
proactive approaches. The program supplies technical assistance
and information on pollution prevention practices to any farmer
or industry that requests it. This includes requests for
technical assistance in site selection or facility layouts,
information on new technologies or pollution prevention
strategies, and individual site assessments. On-site pollution
prevention assessments for production farms or processing
facilities are available by program staff. The agricultural
program also proactively seeks voluntary involvement and
educational opportunities. Areas where more research or
educational efforts are needed have been identified, and the
program serves as a catalyst for initiating and conducting these
types of projects. Additionally, specific elements of the program
are focused on enhancing the understanding and enlisting the
support of various agricultural organizations and agribusinesses
in promoting pollution prevention practices. </p>
<p>The Agricultural Pollution Prevention Program has accomplished
many objectives since its inception in late 1994. An initial
project was the development of two position papers that focused
on identifying the opportunities and impediments for pollution
prevention in agricultural crop production and livestock
production. These papers will serve to focus the program on
priority issues. The program has also been actively providing
technical assistance to the agricultural community. Some examples
include the development of nine publications, five news articles,
and a quarterly newsletter, responses to over 80 requests for
technical assistance resulting in over 30 site visits,
participation in 11 different training sessions for a variety of
audiences, and presentations at more than 30 conferences or
exhibitions with more than 240,000 potential contacts.
Additionally, the program is active in several applied research
projects and has developed working relationships with much of the
agricultural community leadership. </p>
<p><a name="Horticultural"><strong>Pollution Prevention Program
for the Horticultural (Green) Industry</strong></a></p>
<p>P&#178;AD has awarded two applied research grants to the
University of Georgia's agricultural experimental station in
Griffin for a horticultural demonstration project. This grant
money will be used to support the development of a 65 acre tract
of land to become The Georgia Station Research and Education
Garden. The Garden will be developed with input from the
horticultural industry and directed towards industry, gardener,
and homeowner needs with emphasis on interpretation of ongoing
research. The goals of the Garden include: </p>
<ul>
    <li>Develop innovative programs that interpret research for
        the horticultural industry, homeowners, professional
        educators, gardeners and students. </li>
    <li>Develop the Garden as a stimulating location for
        educational and professional opportunities. </li>
    <li>Establish positive community relationships and facilitate
        community involvement in Garden programs. </li>
    <li>Develop a state-of-the-art research and educational
        facility with a secure funding base for Garden programs. </li>
</ul>
<p>A team of scientists has formed a working group to solve
problems for the ornamental plant industry, especially those
prevalent in the humid southeast. Areas of research will include
the following: </p>
<ul>
    <li>Create environmentally sound management practices. </li>
    <li>Maximize plant quality and/or adaptability for the needs
        of the end users.</li>
    <li>Improve technical and economic efficiency of commercial
        ornamental plant production and marketing. </li>
    <li>Communicate research-based recommendations to the green
        industry. </li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3><a name="Public Sector">Public Sector</a> </h3>
<p>To broaden the Division's services to include the general
public, P<sup>2</sup>AD's mission has been expanded to address
the issues of household hazardous waste, used automotive fluids,
and radon. </p>
<p><a name="HHW"><strong>Household Hazardous Waste</strong></a><strong> </strong></p>
<p>Household hazardous waste (HHW) is a product which is
discarded from a home or a similar source that is either
ignitable, corrosive, reactive, or toxic. Examples of common
household hazardous wastes are oil-based paint, batteries,
cleaners, and pesticides. It is estimated that 1.6 million tons
of municipal solid waste disposed of per year is household
hazardous waste, or between 0.3 - 0.5% of the total municipal
solid waste stream. The numbers vary depending on the region and
the season. The number of household hazardous waste collection
programs in the U.S. has increased from 2 in 1980 to 1,648 in
1994. Based on a statewide household hazardous waste survey to
determine the storage and disposal habits of Georgians, the
majority of Georgians stated that they disposed of unwanted
household hazardous products in their trash. Most polled
indicated that the reason that they had leftover hazardous
products in their home was that they had bought too much. The
demographic information from the survey is being used to target
specific audiences that mismanage or improperly dispose of
household hazardous waste. </p>
<p>A common approach to handling HHW in many communities is
collection at recycling or drop off facilities. The high cost of
sponsoring an event and the low participation rates are two
negative aspects of collection which make this approach suspect
as a practical and economically feasible method. P<sup>2</sup>AD
is taking an innovative approach to addressing the issues
associated with improper management of household hazardous waste.
In keeping with P<sup>2</sup>AD's founding philosophy of
prevention, P<sup>2</sup>AD is focused on prevention and proper
management of household hazardous waste. The concept is simple.
Collection does not solve the problem of improper management of
household hazardous waste or encourage alternative management
methods (i.e. reuse or recycling), but only acts as a
afterthought or control mechanism to correct the mismanagement or
inefficient use of hazardous household products. Prevention
reduces or eliminates waste, thereby diminishing the need for
collection. </p>
<p>A Household Hazardous Waste Work Group was convened in January
1995 to study household hazardous waste issues and make
recommendation to the Division's Director about the feasibility
of a state-sponsored program which would reduce household
hazardous waste generation in Georgia. The recommendations were: </p>
<ol>
    <li>P<sup>2</sup>AD should serve as the lead state agency for
        HHW prevention and management. </li>
    <li>P<sup>2</sup>AD should develop guidelines for conducting
        HHW prevention and management programs. </li>
    <li>P<sup>2</sup>AD should promote pollution prevention of
        HHW through various public education programs. </li>
    <li>P<sup>2</sup>AD should fund several pilot household
        hazardous waste collection programs in the state, as
        funds are available.</li>
    <li>P<sup>2</sup>AD should promote collection of various
        problem HHW items. </li>
</ol>
<p>The Division's HHW activities up to the present are based on
the first three recommendations offered by the HHW Work Group.
The Division is using the work group's recommendations as
guidance to develop the format of the household hazardous waste
prevention and management (HHWP&amp;M) program. </p>
<p>It is P<sup>2</sup>AD's intention to work through local
governments to educate and inform the citizens in the state about
household hazardous waste issues. The Division is working with
UGA's Vinson Institute of Government in developing a
&quot;Household Hazardous Waste: Best Management Practices&quot;
handbook. The handbook is designed for use by local governments
to assist officials in answering citizen's inquiries about
household hazardous waste. Another handbook will be developed to
provide guidance to local governments on developing household
hazardous waste programs. In addition to the materials developed
for local governments, the Division will develop materials to
educate the public about the prevention and proper management of
household hazardous waste. </p>
<p><a name="Auto"><strong>Automotive Fluids</strong></a> </p>
<p>Over 200 million gallons of used motor oil are generated
annually by the 45 million Americans who change their own motor
oil in their cars and trucks, better known as the
do-it-yourselfers (DIYs). In 1991, DIY used oil amounted to about
15 percent of the total oil generated by all sources, but 50
percent of all the used oil that was improperly disposed of
originated from DIYs. Improper disposal of just one gallon of oil
can make one million gallons of water undrinkable. Oil and
antifreeze are also toxic to animals and marine life. Handling of
used automotive fluids by DIYs is largely unmonitored and
unregulated. However, as of 1995, 30 states and the District of
Columbia had some type of state-sponsored used oil program that
addressed the DIY population. </p>
<p>It is estimated that about 19 million gallons of passenger car
motor oil are sold in Georgia annually. Much of this oil is
purchased by DIYs. About 5.5 million oil filters are also bought
by DIYs each year in Georgia. Based on national statistics, as
much as five million gallons of used oil may be improperly
disposed of in Georgia annually. Spent filters may also be a
significant waste stream, as national statistics indicate that
approximately 90 percent of used filters are thrown into the
trash rather than being recycled. In Georgia, the state's role in
promoting recycling programs for automotive fluids and filters
has been limited. </p>
<p>In a discussion with EPD concerning household hazardous waste,
EPD requested that P<sup>2</sup>AD take on the responsibility for
the used automotive fluids program. An Automotive Fluids Work
Group was convened in late 1995 by P<sup>2</sup>AD to provide
recommendations for creating a voluntary, state-sponsored program
that would encourage the proper recovery of consumer-generated
used automotive fluids and oil filters. A statewide household
hazardous waste survey conducted by the Division in 1995
indicated that only 49% of Georgians who change their own oil
take the used oil to a collection point for recycling. The
recommendations of the work group are shown below, and are also
contained in the actions detailed later in this plan. The
recommendations were: </p>
<ol>
    <li>P<sup>2</sup>AD should &quot;benchmark&quot; all existing
        DIY collection locations within the state, and identify
        areas of inadequate collection capacity. </li>
    <li>P<sup>2</sup>AD should advertise the location of DIY
        collection sites to the public. </li>
    <li>If deemed necessary by the director, P<sup>2</sup>AD
        should sponsor legislation to put a fee on oil to fund
        the used automotive fluids program. </li>
    <li>P<sup>2</sup>AD should determine if incentives for
        participation in the used automotive fluids program are
        needed for retailers and/or the public. </li>
    <li>P<sup>2</sup>AD should establish a comprehensive
        education program to promote collection of used
        DIY-generated automotive fluids and filters in Georgia. </li>
    <li>P<sup>2</sup>AD should attempt to clarify problems with
        legislation and regulations that hinder proper management
        of used automotive fluids. </li>
</ol>
<p>An unknown quantity of antifreeze is sold to DIYs in Georgia.
However, the HHW survey mentioned above indicated that 47% of
people who service their own cars changed their antifreeze. The
most common methods of disposal for used antifreeze were to pour
it on the ground or put it in the trash. </p>
<p>Currently, used automotive fluid collection points in Georgia
are mainly located at businesses and local governments that
volunteer to collect these fluids and filters, and they are not
required to report the amounts collected or recycled. P<sup>2</sup>AD
has &quot;benchmarked&quot; the existing DIY collection
locations, and has prepared a comprehensive listing of locations
for recycling of oil, filters, and antifreeze. </p>
<p><a name="Radon"><strong>Radon</strong></a> </p>
<p>According to the Surgeon General, radon is the second leading
cause of lung cancer in the United States. Furthermore, the U.S.
Congress' long-term goal for radon is to have the indoor radon
levels be no higher than levels outside. A survey conducted by
EPA during Winter 1988/1989 concluded that 15% of the homes in
North Georgia revealed concentrations of radon greater than 4
picocuries per liter (pCi/L). Less than 10% of the homes tested
in the rest of the state had measurements greater than 4pCi/L.
One county had several schools with all of the classrooms' radon
levels greater than 4pCi/L. </p>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD will serve as the lead state agency for radon.
The Division assumed the responsibility from the Department of
Human Resources under the written approval of the Governor. The
mission of the Division's radon program is to inform the public
about the health risks associated with radon, to increase
awareness about and encourage testing for radon, and to support
local government efforts to address radon issues in their
communities. </p>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD will work closely with all agencies and
organizations that are either involved or interested in providing
radon programs. P<sup>2</sup>AD will coordinate with the
Association County Commissioners of Georgia (ACCG) to solicit
local government support for radon programs, develop and
disseminate information to local governments, and provide
technical assistance to local governments on radon-related
issues. P<sup>2</sup>AD will also provide financial assistance to
local governments in the form of a matching grant. </p>
<hr>
