<h1 align="center"><img
src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/p2ad.gif"
align="absmiddle" width="100" height="100"><font color="#008040">Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division</font></h1>
<h2 align="center">Partnerships</h2>
<hr>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD uses existing resources through innovative
public-private partnerships with the university system; federal,
state, and local government agencies; industry and trade
associations; and non-profit organizations to enhance the spread
of pollution prevention throughout the state. Existing
partnerships include:</p>
<ul>
    <li><a href="#GEP"><strong>The Georgia Environmental
        Partnership</strong></a></li>
    <li><a href="#NICE3"><strong>National Industrial
        Competitiveness through Energy, Environment, and
        Economics</strong></a></li>
    <li><a href="#Ag"><strong>Agriculture Pollution Prevention
        Program</strong></a></li>
    <li><a href="#Locgov"><strong>P2AD and Local Government
        Pollution Prevention Programs</strong></a> </li>
    <li><a href="#NEP"><font color="#000000"><strong>Neighborhood
        Environmental Partnership</strong></font></a></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p><a name="GEP"><strong>The Georgia Environmental Partnership</strong></a></p>
<p>The Georgia Environmental Partnership (GEP) teams P<sup>2</sup>AD,
the Georgia Institute of Technology's Economic Development
Institute (EDI), and the University of Georgia's (UGA) Department
of Biological and Agricultural Engineering to coordinate the
delivery of environmental solutions to Georgia business through a
regionally-based technical assistance network. GEP also works
closely with the Southeastern Environmental Resources Alliance
(SERA) to facilitate the transfer of Department of Energy (DOE)
and Department of Defense (DOD) technologies to the private
sector for commercial application to pressing environmental
problems. </p>
<p>For more information about SERA, visit their web site at <a
href="http://www.augusta.net/~sera">http://www.augusta.net/~sera</a></p>
<hr>
<p><a name="NICE3"><strong>National Industrial Competitiveness
through Energy, Environment, and Economics</strong></a> </p>
<p>The U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) and the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency (EPA) have combined to sponsor an innovative,
cost-sharing program to promote National Industrial
Competitiveness through Energy, Environment, and Economics. The
grant program, known as NICE<sup>3</sup>, provides funding to
state/industry partnerships for projects that develop and
demonstrate advances in energy efficiency and clean production
technologies. Since 1991, NICE<sup>3</sup> has sponsored 26
projects, totaling $7.8 million of DOE funding. </p>
<p>Industry applicants must submit project proposals through a
state energy, pollution prevention, or business development
office. P&#178;AD is an administrator for the program in Georgia
and chooses projects by evaluating them with the criteria
provided. Funds are awarded to state/industry partnerships that
can match DOE/EPA federal funds dollar for dollar. Awardees
receive a one-time grant of up to $400,000 for the proposed
project. After the initial funding, the awardee is expected to
commercialize the process or technology. P&#178;AD has partnered
with the companies listed below on two NICE<sup>3</sup> projects: </p>
<p align="center"><strong>NICE</strong><sup><strong>3</strong></sup> </p>
<table border="0" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td align="center" width="33%"><strong>Grant Recipient </strong></td>
        <td align="center" width="33%"><strong>Project </strong></td>
        <td align="center" width="34%"><strong>Cost Sharing
        Partners</strong></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="33%">Shaw Industries</td>
        <td width="33%">Demonstration of Automated Dyebath Reuse
        in Carpet Manufacturing</td>
        <td width="34%">Shaw Industries, Georgia Institute of
        Technology, Georgia Research Alliance, P&#178;AD </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="33%">Altex Technologies Corporation</td>
        <td width="33%">Assessment of the Feasibility of Advanced
        Mineral Calciner For Lime Regeneration in Pulp and Paper
        Manufacturing</td>
        <td width="34%">Altex Technologies Corp., Weyerhaeuser
        Corporation, J.C. Steele, Incorporated, Industrial Gas
        Technology Commercialization Center </td>
    </tr>
</table>
<hr>
<p><a name="Ag"><strong>Agriculture Pollution Prevention Program</strong></a> </p>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD also teams with the University of Georgia's
Department of Biological and Agricultural Engineering and the
Cooperative Extension Service to promote pollution prevention
practices to agribusiness and the individual farmer using
outreach, environmental assessments through Farm*A*Syst, and
applied research.</p>
<p><em>Horticultural Demonstration Project </em></p>
<p>P&#178;AD has awarded a grant to the University of Georgia's
Agricultural Experimental Station in Griffin for a horticultural
demonstration project. This grant money will be used to support
the development of a 65 acre tract of land to become The Georgia
Station Research and Education Garden. The Garden will be
developed with input from the horticultural industry and directed
towards industry, gardener, and homeowner needs with emphasis on
interpretation of ongoing research. </p>
<p>A team of scientists has formed a working group to solve
problems for the ornamental plant industry, especially those
prevalent in the humid southeast. Areas of research will include
the following: </p>
<ul>
    <li>Create Environmentally Sound Management Practices -
        Research will include ways to reduce chemical usage by
        development of alternative methods of pest control, more
        efficient usage of chemicals, compatibility of
        alternative pest management strategies with other
        horticultural practices , and disposal and recycling of
        solid and liquid waste. </li>
</ul>
<ul>
    <li>Maximize Plant Quality And/Or Adaptability For The Needs
        Of The End Users - Research will be done on selecting and
        breeding plants that are adaptable to specific
        environments. Issues addressed will include: reliance on
        chemicals, cold hardiness, water use, environmental
        impact, and modification of plant production. </li>
</ul>
<ul>
    <li>Improve Technical And Economic Efficiency Of Commercial
        Ornamental Plant Production and Marketing - Areas of
        study involve development of alternative application
        systems to reduce chemical usage and human exposure while
        increasing reliability of coverage and efficiency. </li>
</ul>
<ul>
    <li>Communicate Research-Based Recommendations To Industry -
        Specialists will transfer research results into
        commercial production practices. The Garden will be
        developed to showcase ongoing research and results for
        the benefit of industry, homeowners, and students
        interested in ornamentals. </li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p><a name="Locgov"><strong>P</strong><sup><strong>2</strong></sup><strong>AD
and Local Government Pollution Prevention Programs</strong></a></p>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD is currently undertaking outreach efforts to
inform local governments about the role of the Division and its
services. The Division is involved in ongoing relationships with
the Georgia Municipal Association (GMA) and the Association of
County Commissioners in Georgia (ACCG), and will promote the
creation of local government pollution prevention programs to
these groups' members. P<sup>2</sup>AD will work with interested
local governments to evaluate the feasibility of establishing
programs that encourage a pollution prevention ethic in local
industries, businesses, and within their own county or city
organizations. </p>
<p>The Division also seeks to encourage actions by local
governments such as the following: </p>
<ul>
    <li>Promoting the services of P<sup>2</sup>AD to industries
        and businesses in the local government's area</li>
    <li>Becoming participants in regional pollution prevention
        networking groups to be established statewide in 1997 </li>
    <li>Providing local recognition for businesses and industries
        in their area that are successfully pursuing pollution
        prevention activities</li>
    <li>Serving as a distribution point for educational materials
        aimed at local consumers and civic groups on topics such
        as used oil recycling and household hazardous waste
        prevention and management issues </li>
</ul>
<p>Why Local Government Pollution Prevention? </p>
<p>Local government pollution prevention programs can provide
individual assistance to local industries that augments
assistance provided by state programs such as P<sup>2</sup>AD.
Local government programs can also serve as a catalyst for
pollution prevention activities in the city or county's own
waste-generating operations. Since relationships already exist in
a community between government agencies and businesses,
industries may feel more comfortable requesting assistance from a
local government program. Local government agencies are more
cognizant of a company's culture and specific issues which may
affect a company's decision to implement a suggested alternative.
Individuals within the local government may also be more familiar
with local regulations and permitting requirements which play an
important role in deciding if a pollution prevention alternative
is feasible from a regulatory standpoint. </p>
<p>Local government programs which promote pollution prevention
represent a win-win situation for industries and the community.
By forming partnerships with businesses to encourage pollution
prevention in daily practices, local governments protect their
own community's resources while increasing the competitiveness of
the local employers. For more information on how to start a local
government pollution prevention program, contact Jancie Hatcher
at (404) 651-5120 or 1-800-685-2443.</p>
<hr>
<p><a name="NEP"><font color="#000000"><strong>Neighborhood
Environmental Partnership</strong></font></a></p>
<p><font color="#000000">P<sup>2</sup>AD, the city of Atlanta,
and the Southern Center for Studies in Public Policy of Clark
Atlanta University are working together to address environmental
concerns in Atlanta neighborhoods that exist in close proximity
to manufacturing industries. The U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency is providing funding to assist the development of the
Neighborhood Environmental Partnership (NEP).</font></p>
<p><font color="#000000">The Neighborhood Environmental
Partnership is a collaboration between communities, industries
and government. The NEP seeks to encourage the practice of
pollution prevention and to form community outreach programs.</font></p>
<p><font color="#000000">The NEP is a citywide effort. Two
specific areas have been selected to initiate this partnership
concept - industries and communities within Fulton Industrial and
Marietta Boulevard/Bolton Road corridors.</font></p>
<hr>
<p>Return to <a href="index.htm#p2ad">P2AD Home Page</a></p>
<hr>
</body>
