<body background="Gray_Textured.gif">
<h1 align="center"><img
src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/p2ad.gif"
align="absmiddle" width="100" height="100"><font color="#008040">Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division</font>&#160; </h1>
<h2 align="center">Some Members of P<sup>2</sup>AD's Technical
Staff</h2>
<hr>
<h3><b>Meet </b><a
href="http://ice.bae.uga.edu/dept/faculty/mrisse/index.html"><b>Dr.
Mark Risse</b></a>, our agricultural specialist.</h3>
<hr>
<h3>Paul Crumpler</h3>
<p>Paul received his Mechanical Engineering degree from Georgia
Tech in 1979. His work experience includes 15 years in industry
and government. This experience includes seven years as
mechanical systems and machine design engineer for Michelin Tire
at the Dothan, Alabama facility where he designed mechanical,
thermal, chemical application, and structural systems. Paul has
also designed products for the medical and compressed air
industries and has worked as a consulting engineer designing
industrial HVAC, mechanical, and structural systems. His
pollution prevention experience includes design of particle
collection systems and VOC recovery systems. </p>
<p>In September 1993, he joined the staff of the Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division. Since joining P<sup>2</sup>AD,
Paul has assisted companies in reducing waste by conducting
pollution prevention assessments and employee training. Paul has
assisted a number of facilities including textile, painting,
anodizing, wood products, printing, construction, pulp and paper,
circuit board manufacturing, auto recycling, and vehicle
maintenance operations. </p>
<hr>
<h3>Jancie Hatcher</h3>
<p>Jancie is currently the information manager for the Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division (P<sup>2</sup>AD) in the
Department of Natural Resources. She is responsible for all
operations of the Division's library/clearinghouse and the
production of the Division's quarterly newsletter. She is also
involved with workshop production, training activities, and
various policy work groups. Prior to joining P<sup>2</sup>AD, she
spent several years sampling and performing assessments at
Superfund sites in the Southeast. Jancie is a native of
Chattanooga, Tennessee. She received a bachelor's degree in
chemistry with a minor in biology from Clemson University and a
master's degree in chemistry from Georgia Tech. </p>
<hr>
<h3>Stephanie Siniard</h3>
<p>Stephanie joined the staff of P<sup>2</sup>AD in October of
1993. She is responsible for researching technical requests for
both the public and the staff and serves as a liaison for several
work groups focusing on ground water protection, household
hazardous waste, and recognition of pollution prevention efforts.
Previously, Stephanie served under the Georgia Hazardous Waste
Management Authority as part of the Governor's Intern Program
where she researched and prepared an overview of Household
Hazardous Waste. Stephanie has a Bachelor of Science degree in
Applied Biology from the Georgia Institute of Technology.</p>
<hr>
<h3>Bill Vondersmith</h3>
<p>Bill holds a Bachelor of Science degree in Mechanical
Engineering from the Johns Hopkins University. He has over 30
years of manufacturing experience in the telecommunication
industry working for Western Electric in Baltimore, Maryland and
AT&amp;T in Norcross, Georgia. During most of this time, Bill
held the position of senior process and product engineer with
several assignments covering a wide variety of processes and
product lines including research and development of new products
and processes. Other interim assignments included quality
control, troubleshooting of customer field problems, cost
analysis, and a quality improvement task force. He also spent
several years as a production manager and managed a Manufacturing
Difficulties Investigation Organization.</p>
<p>Bill took an early retirement from AT&amp;T in May 1992. After
three months of retirement, he went to work with the United
States Environmental Protection Agency (U.S.EPA), Region IV in
the Community Right-to-Know/SARA Title III program. Here he
assisted in conducting compliance inspections, chemical safety
audits, outreach presentations, and program planning functions.</p>
<p>In October 1994, Bill accepted a position with the Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division as a Pollution Prevention
Engineer. Since joining P<sup>2</sup>AD, he is working with
companies to evaluate potential pollution prevention
opportunities, analyzing TRI data for P<sup>2</sup> projects,
coordinating GIS mapping support for special projects, and
providing the lead for the transportation sector analysis.</p>
<hr>
<h3>Lisa Ann Kelley</h3>
<p>Lisa Ann Kelley is an Extension Program Specialist with a
focus on Agricultural Pollution Prevention, her current
responsibilities include Farm*A*Syst Coordinator, serving on
Georgia NRCS-USDA (Natural Resource Conservation Service), Whole
Farm Plan Committee, and the Whole Farm Initiatives and Cost
Issues Team, and the Georgia Environmental Agricultural
Sustainability Working Group (GEO). She also serves on the Board
of Directors for the Georgia Environmental Organization (GEO).
The Georgia Agricultural Pollution Prevention Program is a joint
project between the Pollution Prevention Assistance Division,
Department of Natural Resources (DNR) and the Cooperative
Extension Service. </p>
<p>Lisa has a B.S. in Agricultural Science from Auburn University
and a M.S. in Extension Administration, with an emphasis in
Program Development, from the College of Agricultural and
Environmental Sciences at the University of Georgia. Her
professional experience includes work with Agribusiness,
Government Agencies and Non-profits. She was a County Extension
Agent responsible for a county 4-H program, and is still involved
in 4-H as a resource volunteer. Her accomplishments in
Agriculture include holding the American Farmer Degree (FFA), The
Alabama Poultry Federation Service Award, and serving as
collegiate President and Vice President of the former
Southeastern Poultry &amp; Egg Association (now the US Poultry
&amp; Egg Association). Lisa also was an agricultural
spokesperson at the Georgia Agriculture 96, Olympic Venue. </p>
<hr>
<p align="left">Return to <a href="can_do.htm">What can P2AD do
for you?</a></p>
<p align="left">Return to <a href="Index.htm">P2AD Home Page</a></p>
