<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>Industry Recognition Program to Launch in September</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="Gray_Textured.gif">
<h1 align="center"><img
src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/p2ad.gif"
align="absmiddle" width="100" height="100"><font color="#008040">Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division</font></h1>
<h2 align="center">Industry Recognition Program to Launch in
September </h2>
<p align="center">[<em>From the Source - </em>Spring/Summer 1996]</p>
<hr>
<p>P&#178;AD's <a href="p3intro.htm">Pollution Prevention
Partners (P&#179;) program</a> is expected to begin taking
applications from Georgia industry in September. The program is a
three level certification program that recognizes and rewards
continuous pollution prevention performance and improvement by
Georgia industries. Companies that qualify for the P&#179;
program demonstrate to their customers, employees, and community
a commitment to preventing pollution and waste, increasing
efficiency, and improving the environment. </p>
<p>&quot;We view the recognition program as an excellent
incentive for companies to reduce all of their waste
streams,&quot; said Harold Reheis, director of the Georgia
Environmental Protection Division. </p>
<p>&quot;The P&#179; program will recognize companies that are
doing a good job in reducing waste and encourage other companies
to start a pollution prevention program,&quot; said G. Robert
Kerr, director of the Pollution Prevention Assistance Division. </p>
<p>Companies that qualify for the P&#179; program and eligible
for public recognition and other incentives. Among the proposed
incentives is a reduction in certain fees paid to the Georgia
Environmental Protection Division. The fee portion of the program
must be approved by the Governor and General Assembly in 1997. As
companies improve their pollution prevention performance, the
level of recognition and value of the incentives increase.
Companies may qualify for three levels of recognition -- Entry,
Achievement and Model. </p>
<p>The <a href="entintro.htm">Entry Level</a> recognizes
facilities or plants that demonstrate a commitment to developing
a successful pollution prevention program. To qualify, facilities
must develop a pollution prevention plan with numeric reduction
goals. Facilities that qualify for the Entry Level are eligible
for recognition in P&#178;AD publications and will receive a
certificate. Entry Level Partners may apply for advancement to
the Achievement Level after one year. </p>
<p>The <a href="achintro.htm">Achievement Level</a> recognizes
facilities or plants that have established a pollution prevention
program and are making progress toward meeting reduction goals.
Facilities that qualify for and maintain the Achievement Level
will receive public recognition and up to a 10% reduction in
hazardous waste trust fund and Toxic Release Inventory fees paid
to the Georgia Environmental Protection Division (EPD) for one
year. Facilities that continue to show progress toward meeting
pollution prevention goals may receive up to a 10% reduction in
fees in each of two additional years. The savings from these fees
must be allocated to pollution prevention activities at the
facility </p>
<p>The <a href="modintro.htm">Model Level</a> recognizes
facilities or plants that are industry leaders in pollution
prevention. Model Level facilities incorporate pollution
prevention into daily business activities, and have made
substantial progress toward meeting pollution prevention
reduction goals. Facilities that qualify for and maintain the
Model Level will receive public recognition and up to a 25%
reduction in hazardous waste trust fund and Toxic Release
Inventory fees paid to EPD for one year. Facilities that continue
to show progress toward meeting pollution prevention goals may
receive up to a 25% reduction in fees in each of two additional
years. The savings from the fees must be allocated to pollution
prevention activities at the facility. </p>
<p>The program will undergo a public comment period from June 15
to July 15. Applications will be available through P&#178;AD on
September 15. </p>
<hr>
