<hr>
<p align="center"><strong>MISSION STATEMENT</strong></p>
<p align="center"><strong>Recognition Criteria Work Group </strong></p>
<p>The Pollution Prevention Assistance Division (P<sup>2</sup>AD)
of the Department of Natural Resources was created to develop
programs and activities which encourage Georgia industries to
implement sound pollution prevention programs. P<sup>2</sup>AD's
legislation establishes that participation by industry in the
Division's programs and activities is to be voluntary, and that
proprietary information and reports developed for industry will
remain confidential.</p>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD has learned that industry considers many
pollution control and other regulations to be a disincentive to
voluntary pollution prevention, and that awards and recognition
are incentives.</p>
<p>The mission of the Recognition Criteria Work Group (RCWG) is
to develop and recommend to the Director of P<sup>2</sup>AD
pollution prevention recognition criteria. Specifically, the work
group is to: 1) develop criteria by which a company would be
judged to have achieved a level of excellence in the development
and implementation of pollution prevention programs which would
qualify the company for a &quot;Certificate of Excellence&quot;;
2) develop criteria by which a company would be judged to have
achieved a greater level of excellence which would qualify the
company for a &quot;Governor's Award&quot;; and 3) develop both
performance criteria for rating a pollution prevention program
and a process through which the Director can request that EPA
and/or EPD reduce regulatory monitoring and reporting
requirements of a company which can verify, by independent
review, achievement of the required level of performance in
pollution prevention. </p>
<p>The above criteria can be qualitative and/or quantitative, the
same or different for each mission objective.</p>
<p>The work group is requested to review current literature on
OSHA and EPA recognition programs, work of the National Academy
of Standards, and other states' programs. The work group is
further requested to solicit and consider public input. The first
task to be completed by the work group is a work plan and
schedule.</p>
<p>Mr. Lee Thomas of Georgia Pacific, Inc. is to serve as chair
of the RCWG. Peter Bonacum, Roy Bowen, Steve O'Day, Elizabeth
Brock, Win Hill, Bob Woodall, Laurie Fowler, David Word, Rep.
Denny Dobbs, Carol Foley, Pete Howard, Bruce Miller, and Wesley
Wolff are to serve as members.</p>
<p>The work group is created by the Director of P<sup>2</sup>AD,
and is advisory to the Director. The work group is to dissolve
upon completion of its mission.</p>
<p>Bill Wells, P<sup>2</sup>AD's Public Information Director,
will serve as principal staff support to the work group and as
liaison for the Director. </p>
<hr>
<p align="center"><strong>INTRODUCTION</strong></p>
<p>The Recognition Criteria Work Group was created by the
Director of the Pollution Prevention Assistance Division of the
Department of Natural Resources to recommend guidelines for a
state-sponsored pollution prevention recognition program. The
work group acts in an advisory capacity to the Director.</p>
<p>The work group's mission was to recommend criteria by which a
company would be judged to have achieved a level of excellence in
the development and implementation of pollution prevention
programs. The work group was to recommend criteria by which a
company could qualify for a &quot;Governor's Award.&quot; The
work group was also to recommend a process by which the Director
can request that EPD reduce regulatory monitoring and reporting
requirements of those companies which have achieved a required
level of performance in pollution prevention and maintained
compliance with federal, state and local environmental laws and
regulations.</p>
<p>To accomplish its mission, the work group held three meetings.
The members reviewed pollution prevention recognition programs in
other states, recognition programs of federal agencies, existing
pollution prevention/environmental reporting requirements in
Georgia, and components of a successful pollution prevention
program.</p>
<p>The work group was made up of 14 citizens representing a cross
section of industry, government and environmental groups. The
work group members are Lee Thomas, Chairman; Peter Bonacum, Roy
Bowen, Elizabeth Brock, Rep. Denny Dobbs, Laurie Fowler, Carol
Foley, Win Hill, Pete Howard, Bruce Miller, Steve O'Day, Wesley
Wolff, Bob Woodall and David Word.</p>
<hr>
<p align="center"><strong>RECOMMENDATIONS</strong></p>
<p>The Recognition Criteria Work Group recommends that the
Pollution Prevention Assistance Division establish a program for
recognizing and rewarding exemplary efforts in the area of
pollution prevention. The underlying objective of the program
should be to encourage pollution prevention in Georgia industries
by recognizing companies that successfully practice pollution
prevention. The recognition program should foster a common agenda
of preventing pollution and waste, increasing efficiency and
improving the environment.</p>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD should work with the Georgia Legislature and
environmental regulators to create meaningful incentives for
companies which practice pollution prevention. However,
incentives would not lessen or interfere with environmental laws
or rules.</p>
<p>The recognition program should not be overburdensome. Whenever
possible, P<sup>2</sup>AD should use existing required
environmental reports as a basis for determining those eligible
for recognition. A company's environmental compliance history
should be considered during the recognition evaluation process.
The program should be at the facility level.</p>
<p>These recommendations should be used as a guide as P<sup>2</sup>AD
develops the requirements of the recognition program. P<sup>2</sup>AD
should continue to involve the public in the development of the
program. In order for the recognition program to become
successful and achieve its objective of encouraging pollution
prevention, it must be embraced by industry, government and the
general public.</p>
<hr>
<p align="center"><strong>CATEGORIES OF AWARDS</strong></p>
<p>The Recognition Criteria Work Group recommends the formation
of two categories of recognition: a certification program and the
Governor's Award. The certification program should recognize and
reward continuous performance and improvement. It should have
three levels of recognition based on performance and
accomplishment and be measured against criteria developed by P<sup>2</sup>AD.
The three levels in order of increased achievement are: entry,
achievement, and model. Each level would have its own specific
criteria defined by P<sup>2</sup>AD.</p>
<p>At every stage of certification, P<sup>2</sup>AD should, in
consultation with EPD, develop criteria which would establish
that the applicant company is in environmental compliance. A
company must participate in the certification program to be
eligible to participate in the Governor's Award program. The
Governor's Award program recognizes outstanding pollution
prevention projects by a company, individual, organization,
academia, or a government agency. Unlike the certification
program, the Governor's Award should be competitive.</p>
<hr>
<p align="center"><strong>CERTIFICATION PROGRAM</strong></p>
<p>The certification program is comprised of three levels. Each
level is based on a company's level of commitment to, and
achievement in the area of pollution prevention. The first level
is the Entry Level. In order to be recognized as an Entry Level
participant, a company must meet certain criteria that
demonstrate their interest in, and commitment to, developing a
pollution prevention program. These criteria include the
following:</p>
<ul>
    <li>An employee awareness program </li>
    <li>A clear understanding of pollution prevention </li>
    <li>Management and employee commitment </li>
    <li>Established pollution prevention goals </li>
</ul>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD should develop a mechanism which would allow
it to determine if an applicant meets the above criteria and is
in compliance with all federal, state and local environmental
laws and regulations. Certification in the Entry Level program
would be renewable annually based on sustained performance.</p>
<p>The Achievement Level is the second level in the certification
program. The Achievement Level is designed to recognize companies
that have implemented a pollution prevention program. Companies
which obtain the Achievement Level incorporate pollution
prevention into their business activities and can demonstrate
commitment on the part of management to encourage pollution
prevention practices outside the company. A company must have
participated in the Entry Level for at least one year to be
eligible to apply for the Achievement Level. The criteria for the
Achievement Level includes the following in addition to the
criteria for the Entry Level:</p>
<ul>
    <li>Documented reductions of emissions and waste through
        pollution prevention. </li>
    <li>Accounting for all costs and benefits of the company's
        pollution prevention program. </li>
    <li>Reduced and/or more efficient use of resources. </li>
    <li>A community involvement/outreach program. </li>
</ul>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD should develop a mechanism which will allow it
to determine if an applicant meets the above criteria and is in
compliance with all federal, state and local environmental laws
and regulations. Certification in the Achievement Level program
would be renewable annually based on sustained performance.</p>
<p>The Model Level, the third level of the certification program,
is the highest level of achievement. Companies in this category
are considered best-in-class facilities that have exemplary
pollution prevention programs and are recognized as industry
leaders and environmental stewards within their community. To
these companies pollution prevention is not just a commitment but
a practice which is incorporated into all business decisions.
Model Level participants not only instill the pollution
prevention ethic in their employees and vendors, but encourage
others in the community or their industry to incorporate
pollution prevention practices into their daily activities. After
two years at the Achievement Level, a company is eligible to
apply for the Model Level. In addition to meeting the criteria of
the Entry Level and Achievement Level, Model Level candidates
must:</p>
<ul>
    <li>Foster a pollution prevention ethic that extends outside
        the boundaries of the company or facility. </li>
    <li>Employ practices that prevent the transfer of pollution
        to other facilities. </li>
    <li>Serve as a witness for pollution prevention practices to
        peers and the public. </li>
    <li>Assist other companies through pollution prevention
        technology transfer. </li>
    <li>Demonstrate a commitment to pollution prevention in
        product development and purchasing decisions. </li>
</ul>
<p>P<sup>2</sup>AD should develop a mechanism which will allow it
to determine if an applicant meets the above criteria and is in
compliance with all federal, state and local environmental laws
and regulations. Certification in the Model program would be
renewable annually based on sustained performance.</p>
<p>&#160;<strong><u>Application Process</u></strong></p>
<p>Applications for the certification program should be accepted
year round. After receiving the application, the staff should
determine if the company meets the established criteria. Upon
approval, the company's compliance history should be reviewed.
Companies which have favorable compliance histories will receive
a letter announcing their acceptance in the certification
program. </p>
<p>Any company not wishing to continue to participate in the
program may withdraw. </p>
<p>&#160;<strong><u>Qualifications</u></strong></p>
<p>The certification program is open to any company that is
located in Georgia. A company or organization interested in
participating should submit an application. A company or
organization could be nominated by another party. Pollution
prevention projects and programs should address all media types
(i.e., air, solid waste, water). </p>
<p>&#160;<strong><u>Forms of Recognition</u></strong></p>
<p>Companies that achieve certification should be publicly
recognized. P<sup>2</sup>AD should develop a method for informing
the public of the certified company's achievement. Companies that
reach the Achievement Level or Model Level should be eligible for
some type of regulatory and/or financial incentives in the form
of reduced fees, expedited permitting or reduced reporting or
inspections. P<sup>2</sup>AD should consult with EPD to develop
regulatory incentives. If necessary, P<sup>2</sup>AD and EPD
should propose legislation to provide for regulatory incentives.</p>
<hr>
<p align="center"><strong>GOVERNOR'S AWARD PROGRAM</strong></p>
<p>The Governor's Award for pollution prevention should recognize
special and significant pollution prevention achievements of
companies and organizations in Georgia.</p>
<p>The Governor's Award unlike the certification recognition
program should be an annual competitive award given to a company,
individual, or organization that has demonstrated excellence in
pollution prevention. A company should have participated in the
certification program at some level to be eligible for the annual
Governor's Award. This criteria would not apply to individuals,
academia, non-profit organizations or government. The award
should be presented in three categories. These categories should
be small and medium business, large business, and community
(private/individual/organization/government). There should be no
limits on the number of honorable mention certificates presented.</p>
<p>&#160;<strong><u>Application Process</u></strong></p>
<p>The application process for the Governor's Award should be
similar to that of the certification recognition program. The
first step should be a screening of all applicants to eliminate
those which are not eligible. P<sup>2</sup>AD should also review
the applicant's compliance history where applicable. Qualified
applications should be judged by a panel of judges including
industry peers and representatives from relevant state agencies
and universities. </p>
<p>&#160;<strong><u>Qualifications</u></strong></p>
<p>All eligible projects should have occurred during the calendar
year; or in the case of ongoing programs, new activities should
have occurred during the calendar year. Prior recipients are
eligible to compete for the Governor's Award the following year,
although the project must differ from the previous entry. Only
those companies who participate in the certification program
should be eligible for the Governor's Award. This would not apply
to individuals, academia, non-profit organizations or government.</p>
<p>Reductions that are the result of a process being eliminated
or transferred to another facility out of state should not
qualify as pollution prevention activities.</p>
<p>&#160;<strong><u>Forms of Recognition</u></strong></p>
<p>The principal award in the Governor's Award program should be
public recognition. The award should be presented to the company
by the Governor at an annual event.</p>
<hr>
<p align="center"><strong>RECOGNITION CRITERIA WORK GROUP </strong></p>
<p align="center"><strong>Membership List</strong></p>
<ul>
    <li>Lee Thomas, Chairman, Georgia Pacific, Atlanta, GA </li>
    <li>Peter Bonacum, Plant Mgr, Merck &amp; Co., Inc., Albany,
        GA </li>
    <li>Roy Bowen, III, President, Ga. Textile Mfg Assoc., Inc.,
        Atlanta, GA </li>
