<h2 align="center"><b><blink>POLLUTION SOLUTIONS</blink></b></h2>
<h3 align="center"><em><b>From the Source - </b></em><b>Spring
1995</b></h3>
<hr>
<p>In the last issue, we asked how you reduced, reused, or
recycled the Styrofoam &quot;peanuts&quot; or other Styrofoam
material from incoming packaging. The following is a list of the
responses that we received.</p>
<p>Suggestions include:</p>
<ul>
    <li>Taking the excess Styrofoam to pack-ship facilities, such
        as MAIL BOX, Etc. </li>
    <li>Working with suppliers to encourage the use of packaging
        material that can be composted. See if vendors will take
        back the Styrofoam. </li>
    <li>Contacting a local recycler</li>
</ul>
<p>Recyclers of Styrofoam &quot;peanuts&quot; and other packaging
material include:</p>
<ul>
    <li>Free Flow*, Atlanta, Georgia, (404) 346-0696</li>
    <li>Tomahawk Recycling, Alpharetta, Georgia, (404) 410-1938</li>
</ul>
<p>* Accepts only clean, dry material. Company makes new
&quot;peanuts&quot; from the waste collected.</p>
<p>Citizens who have packaging material should contact their
local recycling center to see if they collect Styrofoam material. </p>
