<body background="Gray_Textured.gif">
<h1 align="center"><img
src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/p2ad.gif"
align="absmiddle" width="100" height="100"><font color="#008040">Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division</font> </h1>
<h2 align="center"><b><blink>POLLUTION SOLUTIONS</blink></b></h2>
<h3 align="center"><em><b>From the Source - </b></em><b>Summer
1995</b></h3>
<hr>
<p>In the last issue, we asked how you replaced 1,1, 1-
trichloroethane in your cleaning operations. The following is a
list of the responses that we received.</p>
<ul>
    <li>One company kept the contamination out of their process
        by improving their housekeeping, thereby eliminating the
        need to clean. </li>
    <li>Southwire Machinery Division (SMD) in Carrollton replaced
        1,1,1 with an alkaline cleaner that is applied using a
        heated pressure washer system. </li>
    <li>Additional replacements include terpene blends and
        water-based cleaning systems.</li>
</ul>
<p>There is not one drop-in replacement that will work for every
cleaning operation. Disadvantages associated with using an
alkaline solution as well as the other alternatives may exist .
For more information about solvent substitution or how to choose
the best replacement, contact P2AD's Information Manager, Jancie
Hatcher at (404) 651-5120 or 800-685-2443.</p>
