<title>CLEARINGHOUSE PROVIDES SOLVENT ALTERNATIVE</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="Gray_Textured.gif">
<h1 align="center"><img
src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/p2ad.gif"
align="absmiddle" width="100" height="100"><font color="#008040">Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division</font></h1>
<h2 align="center">Clearinghouse Provides Solvent Alternative
Information</h2>
<p align="center">[<em>From the Source - </em>Spring 1995]</p>
<hr>
<p>One of P<sup>2</sup>AD's free technical assistance services
available to YOU is the Pollution prevention Clearinghouse.
Currently the clearinghouse contains approximately 2,000 journal
articles, reports, and documents which focus on pollution
prevention topics for a variety of industries. Below are
abstracts of some representative items about solvent
alternatives. To obtain a free copy of any of these documents,
contact Jancie Hatcher at (404) 651-5120 or 1-800-685-2443.</p>
<h3>Waste Reduction Activities and Options for a Manufacturer of
Fine Chemicals Using Batch Processes</h3>
<p>- Details a case study of a batch chemical manufacturing
plant. Pollution prevention options identified included solvent
recycling and/or reconditioning, modification of chemical
reaction conditions to improve product quality, and other process
modifications.</p>
<h3>EPA Guide to Cleaner Technologies - Alternatives to
Chlorinated Solvents for Cleaning and Degreasing</h3>
<p>- Good reference which includes general information about a
wide variety of commercially available and emerging technologies
that eliminate the use of ozone-depleting chemicals and reduce
the use of high-VOC solvents. The description of each technology
includes benefits of use, how the technology works, operating
features, application, limitations of use, and materials
compatibility.</p>
<h3>Navigating the Solvent Alternatives Maze: How to Choose a
Practical Ozone-Depleting Solvent Alternative for Your
Application</h3>
<p>- General article which details questions to be answered when
a plant decides which alternative to choose. Also includes a
table which rates alternative cleaning methods according to
performance, operational, and regulatory considerations.</p>
<h3>Solvent Waste Reduction Through Process Substitution</h3>
<p>- Case study of metal component manufacturing plant. The
facility replaced its chlorinated solvent vapor degreasers with
an aqueous cleaning process. This modification enabled the
company to eliminate the use of chlorinated solvents in 95% of
their necessary cleaning applications.</p>
<h3>Industrial Solvents Pollution Prevention Handbook</h3>
<p>- Handbook that identifies pollution prevention opportunities
in the use of industrial solvents. Topics covered include the
following: metal parts cleaning, paint/coating operations,
process equipment cleaning, information sources, and vendor
listings.</p>
<h3>Solvents - The Alternatives</h3>
<p>- Details factors to be considered when choosing an
alternative solvent. Also includes a table of aqueous and
semi-aqueous cleaners, suppliers, typical uses, and potential
problems.</p>
<hr>
