align="absmiddle" width="100" height="100"><font color="#008040">Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division</font></h1>
<h2 align="center"><b>What Can P</b><sup><b>2</b></sup><b>AD's
Information Center Do For Me?</b></h2>
<p align="center"><strong>by Jancie Hatcher, Information Manager</strong></p>
<p align="center">[<em>From the Source - </em>Fall 1995]</p>
<hr>
<p>One of the common questions asked of P<sup>2</sup>AD's staff
is &quot;What services can you provide to me and my
business?&quot;. This article is the first in a series which will
answer that question. The focus of this issue's article is on the
Information Center (Center).</p>
<p>The Center strives to be your one-stop source in Georgia for
pollution prevention and source reduction information. One phone
call (404-651-5120 in the Atlanta calling area or 1-800-685-2443
from outside the metro area) will connect you to the Center.
Jancie Hatcher or another staff member will talk with you and get
an understanding for the type of pollution prevention information
you and your business need and want. In addition to providing the
types of information described below, the staff may also refer
you to one of P<sup>2</sup>AD's engineers for consultation or
on-site assistance. If you have Internet access, the Information
Center can be reached through e-mail at: <a
href="mailto:p2ad@ix.netcom.com"><i>p2ad@ix.netcom.com</i>.</a></p>
<p>After you have initially contacted P<sup>2</sup>AD, a wide
variety of resources from the Center are available to you. The
Center includes a library with over 2300 documents, journal
articles, and books pertaining to pollution prevention,
recycling, and household hazardous waste. All documents have been
abstracted and catalogued in a database to allow easy searching
for specific topics. The staff can provide you with a
bibliography of library holdings for your area of interest.
Single copies of most materials or referrals to other sources of
documents (such as EPA's Pollution Prevention Information
Clearinghouse) are also available free of charge. Although
materials do not circulate as in a traditional library, all
materials are available for public access and use during normal
business hours.</p>
<p>In addition to books and reports, the Center also maintains
over 40 current periodical subscriptions. Journals which contain
general environmental topics include Environment Today,
Environmental Solutions, and EPA Environmental Policy Alert.
Topical journals include Industrial Paint &amp; Powder, Pulp
&amp; Paper, and Precision Cleaning, and publications of regional
interest include Georgia Environmental News, Georgia
Environmental Law Letter, and the Atlanta Business Chronicle.
Pertinent pollution prevention articles from these journals are
also listed in the library's database for quick access.</p>
<p>A third part of the Center's collection consists of over 50
videos. There are videos available on such topics as parts
cleaning, solvent alternatives, corporate pollution prevention
programs, and vehicle maintenance. A public viewing area at P<sup>2</sup>AD's
offices is open during normal business hours.</p>
<p>In addition to its in-house resources, the Center also has
access to a wide variety of outside knowledge. The staff
routinely accesses the holdings at the Georgia Tech and Georgia
State University libraries. P<sup>2</sup>AD also uses the
services of the Waste Reduction Resource Center (WRRC), a
regional source for pollution prevention information funded by
EPA and the Tennessee Valley Authority. P<sup>2</sup>AD keeps a
current listing of WRRC's library holdings on computer for easy
identification of pertinent documents they may have that the
Center does not. P<sup>2</sup>AD's staff also use the Internet
(World Wide Web, gopher sites, etc.) to research specific client
needs.</p>
<p>Clearly, the P<sup>2</sup>AD Information Center has a lot of
reference material that could be useful in integrating pollution
prevention into YOUR business! The staff works hard at answering
your pollution prevention questions in a timely manner. We invite
you to try out the Information Center for yourself, and we look
forward to serving you.</p>
<hr>
