<title>P2AD to Recognize Industry P3 Leaders</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="Gray_Textured.gif">
<h1 align="center"><img
src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/p2ad.gif"
align="absmiddle" width="100" height="100"><font color="#008040">Pollution
Prevention Assistance Division</font> </h1>
<h2 align="center">P<sup>2</sup>AD to Recognize Industry P<sup>2</sup>
Leaders</h2>
<p align="center">[<em>From the Source - </em>Summer 1995]</p>
<hr>
<p>An advisory working group has recommended that P<sup>2</sup>AD
establish a program that recognizes and rewards companies that
excel at pollution prevention. The Recognition Criteria Work
Group was created by P<sup>2</sup>AD Director G. Robert Kerr to
recommend guidelines for a state-sponsored pollution prevention
recognition program. </p>
<p>The work group recommended the formation of two categories of
recognition: a certification program and the Governor's Award.
The certification program would be a non-competitive,
multi-tiered program that recognizes continuous performance and
improvement. The three levels in order of increased achievement
would be: entry, achievement, and model. The Governor's Award
program would recognize outstanding pollution prevention projects
by a company, individual, organization, academia, or a government
agency. Unlike the certification program, the Governor's Award
would be competitive. A company's environmental compliance
history would be considered in each recognition category.</p>
<p>The work group recommended that companies that achieve
certification should be publicly recognized. Companies that reach
the achievement or model level should be eligible for some type
of regulatory relief and/or financial incentives in the form of
reduced fees, expedited permitting, or reduced reporting or
inspections. The principal award in the Governor's Award program
should be primarily public recognition.</p>
<p>&quot;The underlying objective of the program should be to
encourage pollution prevention in Georgia industries by
recognizing companies that are good at it,&quot; said Work Group
Chairman Lee Thomas of Georgia Pacific.</p>
<p>&quot;The staff of P<sup>2</sup>AD will now use the
recommendations and continue to work with the public to develop
the recognition program,&quot; said P<sup>2</sup>AD Director Bob
Kerr.</p>
<p>The work group was made up of 14 citizens representing a cross
section of industry, government, and environmental groups. The
work group members are Lee Thomas, chairman; Peter Bonacum, Roy
Bowen, Elizabeth Brock, Rep. Denny Dobbs, Laurie Fowler, Carol
Foley, Win Hill, Pete Howard, Bruce Miller, Steve O'Day, Wesley
Wolff, Bob Woodall, and David Word.</p>
<hr>
<p>Go to <a href="p3intro.htm">Pollution Prevention Partners
Recognition Program Information</a></p>
<p>Go to the <a href="Recogni.htm">Final Report of the
Recognition Criteria Work Group</a></p>
