<html>

<head>
<title>1994 Toxics Release Inventory</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
</head>

<body background="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/whttxtr1.jpg"
bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<p>[ <a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/index.htm">Home</a> | <a
href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/news.htm">What's New</a> | <a
href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/toc.htm">TOC</a> | <a
href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/feedback.htm">Feedback</a> | <a
href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/search.htm">Search</a> ]</p>

<h2><img src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/epd.gif"
align="left" hspace="0" width="100" height="100">Environmental
Protection Division</h2>

<h3 align="left">GA EPD Right-To-Know Office - (404) 656-6905<br>
<strong>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE:</strong></h3>

<h3 align="center">GEORGIA EPD RELEASES<br>
1994 TOXIC RELEASE INVENTORY REPORT</h3>

<p align="left">April 19, 1996 - Atlanta, Georgia. The
Environmental Protection Division (EPD) of the Georgia Department
of Natural Resources has completed the 1994 Toxic Release
Inventory (TRI) report. This report contains information about
releases of certain toxic chemicals. Of the 344 chemicals and 22
compounds listed by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (US
EPA) for inclusion in toxic release tracking, only 159 are found
at any of the 657 Georgia facilities reporting to EPD.<br>
Unlike previous years, the total number of pounds of toxic
chemicals released in Georgia increased in 1994. The overall
increase is only 3%, which does not bring the releases back up to
the level they were in 1992. The overall increase resulted from
an increase in stack emissions of 17%. This growth was due to
emission increases at 18 established facilities. There are three
reasons for the increases: (1) higher production at many
facilities because of the improving economy, (2) companies filing
forms for new chemicals for which they did not have to file in
previous years (some new chemicals are added to the TRI list each
year), and (3) the use of a new set of emission factors by paper
and pulp mills for estimating releases from their facilities.<br>
Despite the increase in total pounds of chemicals released, very
significant strides were made in improving the quality of air in
Georgia. Last year, EPD looked at each release in light of its
potential for harming the human population. This is done by
multiplying the pounds released for each chemical by a factor
based on how toxic that chemical is. This technique produces an
index which reflects both the amount released and the danger it
represents. This can only be done for those chemicals for which
there is enough information on toxicity. For Georgia, this could
be done for 1993 and 1994 for 27 chemicals. The sum or average of
those indexes can then be compared from one year to the next. The
sum or average for this year's indexes is only half of last
year's sum or average.</p>

<p align="left">The radical decrease in this toxicity index
resulted from voluntary reductions by industry of the two
chemicals which, based on the size of their index, should be of
the most concern to Georgia. The two chemicals are chloroform and
tricholoroethylene. Chloroform emissions were cut 50% since 1993,
primarily by substantial reduction of emissions of this chemical
at Georgia-Pacific's Brunswick plant and Stone Savannah River's
Pulp plant. There was also a 90% reduction in chloroform
emissions at ITT Rayonier. Decreases in trichloroethylene
emissions in Georgia resulted from reductions in emissions at
Lockheed Aeronautical Systems, Greenfield Industries, Grumman
Aircraft Systems, and Kato Spring of Georgia.<br>
The fact that the overall toxicity of the releases in Georgia
(for those chemicals for which it could be measured) decreased
dramatically , even though the total number of pounds released
went up, highlights one of the benefits of the TRI program. The
careful tracking of so many chemicals allows companies to make
decisions about their chemical usage so that they can prioritize
the most toxic emissions for reduction, instead of merely
counting the total number of pounds emitted from their
facilities.<br>
For more information <a href="94GATRI.PDF">click here</a>, or a
free copy of the report, please call EPD's Right-To-Know Program
at (404) 656-6905, or write to TRI Report, Environmental
Protection Division, 7 Martin Luther King, Jr. Dr., Room 139,
Atlanta, Georgia, 30334.</p>

<p align="center">### <br clear="left">
